<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trading in the London futures market took its cues from the US where the
release of some confidence data enlivened an otherwise lacklustre day,
writes Peter John.
A strong performance by the US equity and bond markets on Monday night
sparked off an early rise in London which took the FT-SE futures contract
for June to a high of 3,146.
Then the contract traded within an oppressive 19-point range for the rest of
the morning and early afternoon attracting minimal interest.
When dealing began in New York, the release of US consumer confidence
figures reactivated concerns that the Federal Reserve might tighten interest
rates and acted like a bucket of cold water on Treasury, bund and gilt
prices.
As a result, the Liffe contract slipped back sharply to trade at a discount
of about 8 points to cash and some 12 points below the current estimated
fair value.
However, the nervousness proved overdone and in the last half hour of
trading June re-established itself, and closed 9 above cash at at 3,134 with
turnover very thin at just over 10,000 lots.
Traded options volume of 27,793 lots was up on Monday's desultory level.
Guinness saw 2,678 lots changing hands but the volume principally
represented rolling over of contracts from May to August.
</TEXT>
