<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US stocks edge lower as
profits are taken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US blue-chip stocks were mostly lower as investors booked profits after the
previous session's powerful rally, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was 6.24 easier at 3,699.54, while the more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down a scant 0.84 at 451.87 in
moderate activity.
But the secondary markets improved, with the American FE composite up 2.23
at 438.20, and the Nasdaq composite 3.41 better at 734.21.
Stocks opened on a firm note, with the bond market continuing to provide a
favourable backdrop for a sustained improvement in share prices. In part,
the optimism which inspired Monday's surprising 57-point surge by the Dow
industrials carried over into the opening. But equity investors also drew
quiet comfort from the resilience which longer-dated government bonds were
showing in the face of the day's problematic economic data.
The potential obstacle was the Conference Board's April index of consumer
confidence, which came in at 91.7, from a reading of 86.1 in March. The
sharp increase surprised analysts, and suggested the possibility of a spurt
in consumer spending.
Bonds were thrown off kilter by the news, but soon regained their stride,
showing modest gains by midday. At the same time, stocks slipped into
negative territory and stayed there, as mild profit-taking across the board
prevented a rebound to opening levels. Many of the blue chips were showing
modest losses as the session drew to a close, though analysts were generally
pleased that the setback was not more severe.
Corporate earnings were again a driving force in the markets, and most of
the early gains were struck on better- than-expected first-quarter
performances.
Disney jumped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 43 1/2 after the entertainment group
revealed record revenues and net income up 16 per cent in the first quarter.
Elsewhere, Capital Cities/ABC gained Dollars 14 7/8 to Dollars 712 1/8 as it
announced a big jump in net income and strong operating results from the ABC
broadcast network.
In the energy sector, Chevron shed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 90 7/8 after
revealing a 23 per cent slide in net income as a result of low crude oil
prices. Texaco fell Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 64 3/8 and Arco Dollars 1 1/2
to Dollars 97 3/4 . Both groups posted disappointing results the previous
session.
One of the session's biggest casualties was UNUM, an insurance holding
company which had disclosed a slim earning gain before adjustments on
Monday. The stock plummeted Dollars 4 1/4 to Dollars 50 1/4 on volume of
2.1m shares. Tobacco stocks picked up value on the news of an agreement by
BAT Industries to acquire American Brands for Dollars 1bn in cash. American,
which makes Pall Mall and Lucky Strike cigarettes, climbed Dollars 2 3/4 to
Dollars 34 1/2 on the announcement. Philip Morris, the world's leading
marketer of tobacco products, jumped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 54 1/4 . RJR
Nabisco was Dollars  1/2 better at Dollars 6 7/8 . On the Amex, BAT ADRs
improved Dollars 9 1/16 to Dollars 13 3/4 .
Canada
Prices continued to climb in moderate trading. The TSE-300 composite index
rose 27.07 points, or 0.64 per cent, to 4,263.80. The rise followed a
69.57-point jump yesterday.
Advancing issues outpaced declines 460 to 322, volume of 65.01m shares
exceeded Monday's 52.44m shares, and trading value was CDollars 870.1m
compared with CDollars 675.3m.
Industrial products recorded the day's biggest increase, 1.68 per cent. In
that group, Northern Telecom soared 2  5/8 to 41 after reporting slightly
higher first-quarter earnings, with the latest period including a large
gain.
</TEXT>
