<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / International Company News: Hoechst profits up 16% at three
months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Pre-tax profits at Hoechst, one of Germany's big three chemicals groups,
rose 16 per cent in the first three months of this year, climbing by DM70m
to DM506m (Dollars 295.90m).
Although the figures served to underscore the growing optimism in the
European chemicals sector as the industry pulls out of cyclical recession,
Hoechst warned that growth in profits for the full year would be restrained
despite the encouraging start to the year.
Hoechst, which suffered a 42 per cent drop in pre-tax profits last year,
said profits in the quarter benefited from growth in sales volumes in
markets outside Germany as well as the impact of cost-cutting.
But the company said it would have to bear the costs this year of further
restructuring. Last year restructuring charges amounted to DM1bn; the group
has cut 12,000 jobs in the past three years and plans to cut 8,000 more in
1994 and 1995.
It said business was likely to improve and that profits would increase
despite the restructuring costs. The business environment was steadily
becoming more favourable to the company's activities, it said, but recovery
in Germany was very restrained. The muted optimism contrasts with Bayer
which said last month that earnings this year would probably increase by 20
per cent.
</TEXT>
