<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / International Company News: Tenneco to sell 35% of Case unit
via IPO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tenneco, the Texas-based industrial company, is to sell 35 per cent of its
Case farm and construction equipment division in an initial public offering.
The long-awaited announcement, aimed at reducing Tenneco's exposure to
cyclical businesses, comes a day after Varity of the US revealed it is close
to selling Massey Ferguson, a big rival to Tenneco's CaseIH brand in world
tractor markets. Announcement of the sale of Massey to Atlanta-based Agco
could be made today.
Industry analysts estimate the Case IPO will yield about Dollars 500m for
Tenneco, which the company plans to use to repay short-term debt and to
pursue expansion of core businesses and new acquisitions.
Case, Tenneco's largest division, employs 17,000 worldwide. It is the
second-largest tractor producer in the US after Deere, and is second to
Caterpillar in the manufacture of construction equipment in the US.
In Europe, Case is one of the top three companies in the tractor market and
is a significant producer of construction equipment through Case Poclain of
France, of which it owns 98.4 per cent.
Case is enjoying an increasein demand from US farm and construction
industries. In the first quarter, it earned Dollars 81m, nearly matching
profits for full-year 1993 of Dollars 82m. But its European operations
continue to make losses.
Tenneco reported first-quarter operating earnings rose to Dollars 301m or 67
cents a share on sales of Dollars 3.3bn, from year-ago earnings of Dollars
275m or 46 cents on sales of Dollars 3.2bn.
Shares of the new Case Corporation would be listed in New York. Tenneco did
not include an offering price in its filing. Analysts said that with Dollars
1.1bn in equity and Dollars 1.5bn in debt, and projected 1994 earnings of
Dollars 300m, Case Corporation's 70m shares would be priced somewhere in the
range of Dollars 16 to Dollars 24.
</TEXT>
