<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Santander shares fall on Banesto takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Banco Santander, the Spanish banking group, fell 7 per cent in
Madrid yesterday after its successful bid to buy control of Banco Espanol de
Credito (Banesto).
Santander is to finance the Pta281bn (Pounds 1.4bn) acquisition - Spain's
biggest takeover - partly through a Pta89bn rights issue. The new shares
will be offered on the basis of a one for three already held, at a price of
Pta2,250, less than half the current market level.
Santander's share price dropped by Pta440 to Pta5,710. Banesto shares
meanwhile climbed 15 per cent to Pta868, close to their highest point since
the Bank of Spain intervened last December. Other bank shares also rose.
Santander's Pta762-per-share bid for 60 per cent of Banesto's stock far
exceeded most expectations and was well above rival bids from two other
banks. The shares come from a recent recapitalisation, part of a rescue
operation funded jointly by the Bank of Spain and the private banking
system.
Mr Emilio Botn, Santander chairman, said yesterday that part of the
shareholding might be taken up by associated institutions in the UK and the
US. These could include Royal Bank of Scotland, in which Santander holds
just under 10 per cent, and New Jersey-based First Fidelity Bancorp, in
which it has 24.5 per cent stake.
He said Santander intended to keep a stake of at least 40 per cent in
Banesto, after offering 8 per cent of the shares to its own shareholders.
He said the price was 'absolutely reasonable' and claimed the bank had
'sufficient arguments' for maintaining its AA credit rating. However, the
rating agencies IBCA and Standard and Poor's both said they were putting
Santander under review 'with negative implications'.
Mr Botin said Santander should still be able to increase earnings in line
with the trend in the first quarter, when consolidated pre-tax profits rose
9.7 per cent to Pta34.2bn. Banesto was expected to resume paying dividends
in 1997 or 1998.
Mr Alfredo Saenz, the caretaker Banesto chairman who is being kept on in the
job by Santander, said Banesto would focus on standard retail banking
activities.
Background, Page 29
