<DOCNO>FT942-13025</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ED0DLACMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940427
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Water row may drown Scots Tories: A look at the party driven
to say no to privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Conservatives last week began issuing leaflets with the unusual
headline: 'Tories say no to privatisation.' The leaflets emphasised that the
government had no intention of privatising Scotland's water and sewerage
industry in spite of claims to the contrary from opposition parties.
Water has become the big issue in next month's elections for Scotland's nine
regional and three island councils. The regions are due to be abolished in
1996 and replaced by about 30 all-purpose councils absorbing the 53
districts, so councillors elected on May 5 will serve for only two years.
This may have made the election campaign almost invisible on the doorstep,
but has not stopped the parties arguing. The opposition sees the water issue
as a good way of pointing out the ideological differences between themselves
and the Tories.
The subject stirs feelings in Scotland which have little counterpart in
England and Wales where water services are in private hands. Most Scots
believe water is a God-given asset that must be left in public hands. It is
therefore surprising that a government which has taken care since the 1992
general election not to offend the Scots allowed the issue to gain such
momentum. The Conservatives contemplated privatising the Scottish water
industry to manage water services after the abolition of the regional
councils which now run it.
In spite of very early signs from opinion polls that privatisation was
highly unpopular, even with Tories, the government was slow last year to
declare unequivocally that it was off the agenda. Its solution, to create
three publicly owned water authorities, aroused anxiety because they would
not be under local government control and could be privatised later.
In March some 97 per cent of people voting in a referendum in Strathclyde
region, which is centred on Glasgow and contains about half the Scottish
population, said they wanted water to remain in local government hands. The
turnout in this postal ballot was 71 per cent.
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, denounced the referendum as irrelevant.
But two weeks ago he emphasised that councillors would be on the water
authorities' boards, possibly in a majority. The government was not
privatising water 'by the front door, the back door or any other door' and
that would remain the government's policy 'for many years'.
However the opposition shows no wish to drop the idea that the Tories will
privatise water. Mr Alex Salmond, leader of the Scottish National party, was
pictured by a reservoir denouncing privatisation, while Mrs Jean McFadden,
Labour leader of Glasgow district council, wrote in the Glasgow Evening
Times that water privatisation was 'the latest stage in the government's
systematic plundering of public assets for private profit'. Pensioners, she
said, would have to 'think twice before they make a cup of tea'.
The misrepresentation of the Tories' position has probably invigorated their
election campaign, leading them to denounce the opposition for deceit. Yet
they face a tough fight, standing at only 13 per cent in the Scottish
opinion polls, their lowest-ever level, and blamed for income tax rises and
the imposition of VAT on fuel. They control none of the regional councils
and hold only 52 of the 453 regional council seats being contested.
The reform of local government has some, largely silent, supporters outside
the Tory party, but more see it as an attempt by the Conservatives to regain
lost ground in local government by gerrymandering the boundaries of the new
single-tier councils.
Labour dominates local government in the central belt: it controls four
regions - Strathclyde, Central, Fife and Lothian - and governs Tayside
(centred on Dundee) and Grampian (around Aberdeen) in coalition with the
SNP.
Labour is fielding 350 candidates, about the same number as the
Conservatives, but Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, says it
will do well to hold the gains it made in 1990 when it took 44 per cent of
the vote at the height of Tory unpopularity over the poll tax.
The SNP stands at 26 per cent in the opinion polls and thus claims to be the
second party in Scottish politics. It is fielding 370 candidates, more than
any other party, and claims good prospects of becoming the biggest party in
Grampian and Tayside.
Its main challenge is to Labour which it accuses of doing nothing to save
Scottish water and of allowing the Scottish local government bill to
complete its committee stage last week with few significant changes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
