<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / 148 more jobs go at Swan Hunter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A further 148 employees of Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder which is in
receivership, are to be made redundant and 237 will be laid off while the
company fights for more work, it was announced yesterday, Chris Tighe
writes.
The redundancies and lay-offs, to take effect late next month, have been
caused by a gap in workload once the Type 23 frigate HMS Northumberland is
handed over on May 24. Its departure leaves only one vessel at Swan Hunter.
Union leaders regretted the new round of job cuts, but welcomed the decision
of receivers Price Waterhouse to lay off, rather than make redundant, the
majority of the 385 surplus employees. Those affected include manual,
clerical, technical and managerial staff.
Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie, the French company negotiating to buy
Swans, met defence ministry officials yesterday to provide information about
its finances and structure.
