<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Shergar damages case fails
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in the kidnapped Derby winner Shergar yesterday failed in a
High Court attempt for Pounds 200,000 damages over their failure to recover
an insurance pay-out for the loss of the horse.
Racehorse trainer Mr Vincent O'Brien, his wife Jacqueline, Mr John and Mrs
Susan Magnier, and Mr Robert Sangster's Swettenham Stud, as joint owners of
the Coolmore Stud in County Tipperary, bought three Pounds 280,000 shares in
Shergar, prized as a breeding stallion, when he was syndicated by the Aga
Khan in 1981.
They had paid the first instalment of Pounds 100,000 each when the horse -
valued at Pounds 10m - was kidnapped in February 1983, probably by the IRA,
from Ballymany Stud Farm, County Kildare. The horse has never been
recovered.
Insurers at Lloyd's of London refused to pay out under a Pounds 200,000
policy covering two-thirds of the initial instalments because the horse had
been covered only against death, not theft.
The Coolmore shareholders brought a damages claim against bloodstock agent
BBA (Ireland), which had arranged the insurance, and Lloyd's brokers
Hughes-Gibb, which placed the cover with underwriters. They claimed
negligence and breach of duty in failing to ensure that the cover included
theft.
But Mr Justice Rattee ruled that Coolmore had never asked for such cover and
the defendants were not negligent in failing to obtain it.
The action was dismissed and the Coolmore shareholders were ordered to pay
the defendants' legal costs.
</TEXT>
