<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Labour says defence statement is a cover-up: Up to 20,000
redundancies expected; Military bases may merge; Some activities face
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence yesterday released its annual statement on defence
expenditure several months earlier than usual and without the usual
statistical details.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, presented the document as a
commitment to maintaining or even increasing Britain's fighting capacity.
He said that high performance by the armed forces was one of Britain's
greatest strategic assets and would not be compromised. The annual statement
was unusual in containing virtually no change in defence policy.
The timing of the statement prompted a storm of Labour complaints that the
government was covering up its plans for an overhaul of support services in
the armed forces which are expected to involve heavy job losses.
Labour MPs said the government was postponing announcements of large cuts
and heavy redundancies until after the local and European elections.
Labour criticised the document for failing to give details of the cuts which
would come from the review of costs, which is called Front Line First.
Mr Rifkind confirmed that more than 30 separate studies of possible savings
were under way and that the defence ministry was studying more than 3,000
proposals for saving money from its own workforce and ordinary service
staff. However, no final decisions had been made.
The minister said that the breadth and capacity of Britain's armed forces
was matched only by that of the US, Russia and France. Mr Rifkind added that
the government intended to maintain that position.
At the same time, however, he came under attack from Conservative
backbenchers for jeopardising frontline forces through cuts in support
staff.
Front Line First is expected to recommend mergers of bases, privatisation of
some services and up to 20,000 redundancies among support personnel.
Under the proposals Rosyth naval base in Scotland could close, and several
headquarters could be merged. Up to 90,000 vehicles may be leased instead of
owned, and much of the Royal Air Force's maintenance could be handled by
private companies.
Tory MPs expressed deep concern yesterday about the effect of impending cuts
in the defence budget, in spite of Mr Rifkind's assurances. Sir Nicholas
Bonsor, the Tory chairman of the Commons defence select committee, said he
wanted to see what Front Line First would show, but warned that sweeping
cuts in military support staff could reduce frontline effectiveness.
'We have to be very careful that we don't leave our troops unsupported,' he
said. 'We have to make sure that they have real back-up.'
Mr David Clark, Labour's defence spokesman, said: 'This is a whitewash, not
a white paper. The Tories are running scared on defence.'
But Mr Rifkind was supported by Sir Archie Hamilton, a former Tory defence
minister, who said: 'I am being constantly reassured that the the savings
are there.' But he said some proposals would face strong political
opposition.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
FRONT LINE FIRST: THE OPTIONS
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 -Transport vehicles and aircraft leased rather than purchased
 -RAF Logistics Command - current staff 13,000 - scrapped and work
  transferred to private sector
 -Senior officers cut by between 10 per cent and 15 per cent and perks
  such as staff and cars cut back
 -RAF HQ at High Wycombe and army HQ at Wilton merged with Navy HQ at
  Northwood
 -Closure of Rosyth Naval Base
 -Merger of Medical staffs of Army, Navy and Airforce. Staff cut sharply
  from 9,000
 -Procurement executive cut from 11,000
 -Defence intelligence staff cut from 2,000
 -Stores and maintenance bases closed
 -More market testing and contracting out
 -Merger of service training programmes
 -Management of MoD lands to be transferred to private sector
  Cost studies into veterinary, catering, meterological and air traffic
  control departments and chaplaincy, music and uniforms
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Editorial Comment, Page 23
