<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Rosyth closure threatens 2000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Closure of Rosyth naval base in Fife would put 1,600 naval jobs and 400
civilian posts at risk. Its operations have been scaled back in recent years
and the small ships handled there may be transferred to Portsmouth. Rosyth
dockyard would not be affected.
The RAF's support services are also a target because maintenance of aircraft
is particularly labour-intensive and costly.
The Logistics Command employs 13,000 people and could be transferred to the
private sector. Some defence analysts, however, expect a substantially
slimmed-down operation to run in tandem with private-sector maintenance
companies. Other large manpower cuts might include slimming the Procurement
Executive, responsible for buying forces' equipment, and running down
medical and veterinary services.
Old inter-service rivalries may be challenged. Analysts think consolidating
all three staff colleges into a single base at Camberley would be logical.
Staff from the RAF headquarters at High Wycombe and the army headquarters at
Wilton may also be squeezed into a unified command at the Navy's base at
North-wood.
Smaller targets for the MoD knife may include chaplains and music.
</TEXT>
