<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Schools feel the pinch as boarder numbers decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The numbers of boarders in UK schools dropped 5.2 per cent last year as
independent schools continued to be squeezed by the recession.
Following a fall of 6.2 per cent last year, boarding numbers have now
dropped by almost an eighth in two years. However, the Independent Schools
Information Service claimed that the figures, which it released yesterday,
heralded a 'sooner-than-expected recovery' because the number of day pupils
rose 0.1 per cent.
Total pupil numbers fell by 0.96 per cent following a drop of 1.5 per cent
last year.
Mr David Woodhead, director of Isis, said the impact of this month's tax
increases on parents' disposable incomes would now be critical to
recruitment for next September. He said: 'Tax is one of the great
imponderables . . . parents are looking at their choice of schools very
pragmatically.'
The decline was sharpest in boarding preparatory schools. Among boys there
was a drop of 13.4 per cent in 10-year-old boarders from 2,526 to 2,188,
while the number of boarding 11-year-olds fell 10.2 per cent to 3,467.
Mr Roy Chapman, headmaster of Malvern College and chairman of the
Headmasters' Conference, which represents the largest boys' schools, said:
'Boarding schools have to face up to the realities of the marketplace in a
way which they've never done before.'
He added that in those 'halcyon' days schools had 'leapfrogged' each other
to produce new capital developments. Spending on buildings and equipment
peaked in 1991. This year it was cut by 9.6 per cent, from Pounds 513 to
Pounds 468 per pupil.
Rising use of funds from the government's assisted-places scheme, and from
school bursaries and scholarships, emphasised the impact of the recession,
with 127,522 pupils - 27.3 per cent of the total - receiving some aid.
Take-up of the government scheme rose by a further 2.4 per cent, with a
record 32,307 pupils now receiving state help.
Nursery education was the only significant area of growth, with the number
of two-year-olds in independent schools rising 12 per cent from 3,082 to
3,452 while the number of 3-year-olds increased from 9,570 to 10,383.
Heavy marketing in the far east and eastern Europe led to a 10 per cent
increase in foreign pupils coming to the UK - to a record of 6,422 compared
with 5,859 last year. The numbers recruited from continental Europe rose
from 1,537 to 1,796, while recruits from the Far East outside Hong Kong
increased from 1,140 to 1,261.
The drop in numbers occurred in spite of a sharp fall in school fees
inflation, which at an average of 2.6 per cent rose less than national
average earnings for the first time since the survey began in 1983.
But Mr Michael Oakley, chairman of the Independent Schools Bursars'
Association, predicted that fees inflation might increase as private schools
would feel obliged at least to match the 2.9 per cent pay award for state
teachers.
</TEXT>
