<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Review fails to calm fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Few of the uncertainties hanging over the UK's armed forces were resolved by
the white paper yesterday.
The results of Front Line First, the review of defence costs ordered after
the last Budget, will not be published until the end of July, said Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary.
The review is aimed primarily at saving money in the armed forces support
staff and should not affect fighting strength. But base closures,
privatisation of some services and up to 20,000 job losses are expected.
Rosyth naval base in Fife could face closure under the review, putting at
risk 1,600 naval jobs and 400 civilian posts. Its operations have been
scaled back in recent years and the small ships handled there may be
transferred to Portsmouth. Rosyth dockyard would not be affected.
The RAF's support services are also a target because maintainance of
aircraft is particularly labour-intensive and costly.
The Logistics Command employs 13,000 people and could be transferred to the
private sector. Some defence analysts, however, expect a substantially
slimmed-down operation to run in tandem with private-sector maintenance
companies. Other large manpower cuts might include slimming the Procurement
Executive, responsible for buying forces' equipment, and running down
medical and veterinary services.
Leasing vehicles is another possibility. The initiative is unlikely to
extend as far as tanks and the armed forces' stock of 90,000 cars, Land
Rovers and trucks may not be attractive to the private sector. But new
batches of vehicles may be leased from private companies, which would also
be responsible for maintenance.
Old inter-service rivalries may be challenged. Analysts think consolidating
all three staff colleges into a single base at Camberley would be logical.
Staff from the RAF headquarters at High Wycombe and the Army HQ at Wilton
may also be squeezed into a unified command at the Navy's base at Northwood.
Smaller targets for the MoD knife may include chaplains and music, though
both may arose strong sentiments. Regimental bands have been protected
before and privatising spiritual support may also face opposition from
Conservative backbenchers. The review team even has a working party studying
the cost of armed forces regulations.
Mr Rifkind yesterday acknowledged that it was a time of uncertainty for
armed forces support personnel, though he emphasised that cuts would not
compromise the effectiveness of front-line forces.
If the review produced savings beyond the Pounds 750m a year by 1997
required by the Treasury, then the Ministry of Defence would be able to
spend the money on improvements to fighting forces.
</TEXT>
