<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Banknote thieves told to pay Pounds 1/2 m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England yester-day won its High Court action against three
former employees whose families it claimed had been living the 'life of
Riley' on more than Pounds 500,000 stolen from its banknote destruction
depot.
But it was believed last night that the Crown Prosecution Service had ruled
out criminal action against Mrs Christine Gibson, 44, Mr Kenneth Longman,
34, and Mr Michael Nairne, 39, because there was insufficient hard evidence
to secure a conviction.
Judge Norman Rudd ruled that the three had systematically stolen cash from
the depot at Debden, Essex, between 1988 and 1992.
He said they had been fully aware of where the money had come from. Their
explanations for their extravagant lifestyles were 'wholly incredible and
totally unsupported'.
It was alleged that Mrs Gibson had smuggled thousands of pounds out of the
depot by stuffing it into her underwear.
Mrs Gibson's husband, Mr Peter Gibson, who the Bank claimed had never done
an honest day's work in his life, sniggered and said 'prat' as the judge
gave his finding.
He ordered the Gibsons to return Pounds 250,000, the Longmans Pounds 150,000
and the Nairnes Pounds 110,000. Enforcement of the judgment was suspended
for 28 days pending an appeal and the Bank was granted a continuation of
asset-freezing orders against the three families.
The families, who are all from Loughton, Essex, were also ordered to pay
costs estimated at Pounds 400,000. The costs order against the Longmans and
the Nairnes was not to be enforced without leave of the court as they were
on legal aid.
Another former Bank employee, Mr Kevin Winwright, admitted three counts of
theft totalling Pounds 170,000 and was jailed for 18 months in January 1993.
</TEXT>
