FT  27 APR 94 / BBC in Polish radio application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC World Service Radio has teamed up with GWR, the Bristol-based commercial
radio group, to apply for a commercial radio licence in Warsaw, Raymond
Snoddy writes.
It is believed to be the first collaboration between a language section of
the BBC World Service and a UK commercial broadcaster.
Under Polish law foreign broadcasters are only allowed to hold a 33 per cent
stake. The two British broadcasters would team up with Zycie Warszawy, the
Warsaw daily newspaper.
GWR, through a subsidiary, Central European Broadcasting - which already has
an interest in a Prague radio station - would probably take a one-third
stake. The BBC would have an option for 10 per cent of that stake. Its main
role, through its Polish section, would be as a news and programme supplier.
The decision on the licence is expected next month.
