<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / 'Spectacular incompetence' alleged at Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's underwriters were guilty of 'incompetence on a spectacular scale' it
was alleged yesterday on the opening day of the UK's biggest legal action to
date, brought by loss-making Lloyd's Names.
Mr Geoffrey Vos QC, representing 3,095 lossmaking Gooda Walker Names, told
Mr Justice Phillips that underwriters had 'wholly ignored the basic, obvious
and accepted principles of the reinsurance market'.
The Gooda Names are seeking compensation of some Pounds 629m from 71
members' agents who placed them with four syndicates formerly managed by the
Gooda Walker agency. The syndicates specialised in catastrophe reinsurance
business, reinsuring other reinsurance companies and Lloyd's syndicates. The
underwriters either 'didn't know the scale of their likely exposures' or had
'wholly ignored it', alleged Mr Vos. They bought 'inadequate' reinsurance
protection and were overwhelmed by losses from a series of catastrophes -
ranging from the Piper oil rig explosion to hurricane Hugo - between 1987
and 1990.
Total losses of the four syndicates - 164, 290, 298 and 299 - in seven
separate years of account amount to more than Pounds 850m.
The outcome of the case, likely to last three months, is expected to be a
pointer to the prospects of thousands more Names planning similar action. A
case by nearly 2,000 Feltrim Names, who were also placed on reinsurance
syndicates, is scheduled to begin in the autumn.
Lloyd's losses since 1988 amount to more than Pounds 7bn. The market expects
next month to report a loss of more than Pounds 2bn for the 1991 year of
account.
'The claim is simple,' explained Mr Vos. 'The plaintiffs allege that each of
the underwriters fell below the standards to be expected of a reasonably
competent underwriter.'
The losses of each of the four syndicates were wholly 'disproportionate'
both in relation to the profits received by Names in earlier years and the
rest of the market. In 1989 the four syndicates' total losses of Pounds 685m
accounted for about 30 per cent of the market's overall loss.
'The aim of reinsurance is to spread the loss. The Gooda Walker syndicates
succeeded in concentrating a large part of the market's losses on their
Names,' added Mr Vos.
'It would be charitable to describe these underwriting methods as gambling,
(but) a roulette player at least knows how much he has put on the table and
how much he can lose.'
</TEXT>
