<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / BCCI official 'withheld data'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An official with the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International
helped to boost the bank's profits artificially by almost Dollars 250m by
manipulating loan accounts, the Old Bailey heard yesterday.
Mr Anthony Evans QC, prosecuting, said Mr Imran Imam, who was an account
officer at BCCI's London headquarters, also withheld crucial information
from Price Waterhouse, the bank's auditors, which allowed a false picture of
BCCI's profitability to be presented to the outside world.
Mr Imam is charged with six offences including two of conspiring to conceal
documents, three of furnishing false information and one of conspiring to
falsify records. He denies all the charges.
Mr Evans said that Mr Imam worked alongside the two most important men in
BCCI - Mr Agha Hasan Abedi, its former president, and Mr Swaleh Naqvi, its
former chief executive.
Although junior to both men, Mr Imam played an important role in the
multi-million-dollar fraud which led to the bank's collapse, he said.
In one part of the alleged fraud, Mr Imam was involved in inflating profits
by falsifying documents relating to loans apparently made to eight wealthy
individuals, Mr Evans said.
These loans were not genuine, he continued. Shares in the Dutch
Antilles-based company Credit and Commerce American Holdings, which were
used as security for the loans, were held by the individuals only as
nominees. Mr Imam was aware of this and failed to report it. Documents also
showed that BCCI never expected the loans to be repaid.
However, the bank's accounts showed that between 1982 and 1989 Dollars 500m
was charged to the bank in the form of interest and fees, Mr Evans said. Of
this, Dollars 248m was charged between 1987 and 1989, the period covered by
the charges against Mr Imam.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
</CO>
<XX>
