<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Clergy income reform planned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New ways of financing pensions for Church of England clergy will be proposed
later this year following an Pounds 800m decline in the Church
Commissioners' income-producing assets, the Commons social security
committee was told yesterday.
Dr George Carey, Archbishop of Canterbury, and other church leaders faced
questioning by the committee as part of its inquiry into the operation of
pension funds.
Under existing arrangements, the commissioners finance clergy pensions out
of annual income.
However Mr Phillip Mawer, secretary-general of the Church of England general
synod, told the committee that if this arrangement continued, pension
liabilities were likely to consume the commissioners' entire asset income by
2010.
The alternative of a contributory scheme is being considered. Present
thinking, said Mr Mawer, was that dioceses rather than individual clergy
should make the contributions.
Dr Carey gave a firm undertaking that the church had 'resources to manage
the pension issue'. Clergy pension rights were not in danger.
The Church of England is being forced to raise more money from parishes
following the heavy decline in the commissioners' assets, due largely to
over exposure in property investments. Dr Carey said that a Financial Times
report which first detailed the commissioners' difficulties two years ago
had been a 'stunning blow to many of us', although he had been aware to some
degree of the seriousness of the problem before that.
</TEXT>
