<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Free-market gunslingers lose their fire: A look at an
organisation true to its code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY and STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As the Institute of Directors prepares for a change of leadership, Britain's
main organisation for business leaders is stoical about its future.
The organisation which chose 'thriving on change' as the theme for
yesterday's annual convention has no plans to do so. The event was only just
saved from being a flop by the vigour of the mid-afternoon speech by Mr
Peter Morgan, the outgoing director-general.
Last year's affair was a hard act to follow, with Mr Bill Gates of Microsoft
among speakers who pulled in some 3,200 delegates. This year's poor
attendance - fewer than the 2,800 delegates registered - was evidence of a
deeper problem for the IoD.
A standard bearer for enterprise, the free market and free trade, the IoD
was in its prime during the Thatcher era. But whereas in the 1980s it was
pushing on an open door in its pleas for de-regulation, it is now meeting
more resistance.
With a member seconded to the Department of Trade and Industry to explore
and promote ways of cutting regulation, the IoD claims it is still scoring
victories for its small-business constituency.
But it admits that the climate has changed. What it disputes is that the
change has made it redundant.
'We are not in a popularity contest,' says Mr Gordon Leak, head of media
communications. 'We are there to represent our members. The political
pendulum is not a factor in the IoD's thinking - principles are.'
The change makes its lobbying function more necessary rather than less so,
it argues. But, more than that, it believes that the nature of the recovery
is going to raise its profile as an educator and promoter of small business.
'Employment in the private sector will never be the same again,' Mr Morgan
declared yesterday, echoing the IoD belief that growth is going to rest
principally on a rise in entrepreneurs.
Where the IoD differs from the resurgent Confederation of British Industry,
it says, is in the IoD's emphasis on the individual.
Its members certainly believe that to be the case. 'The IoD represents the
small businessman, where the CBI is more the organisation for big business
like the ICIs - although the CBI would deny this,' said one delegate
yesterday.
In spite of such loyalty, the IoD has come off the boil, with membership of
about 33,000 in Britain and 48,000 worldwide, down about 5,000 from its
peak. But recruitment is picking up and the IoD can expect to lose fewer
members to bankruptcy.
Holding true to the faith, its loyal core may argue in stronger and stronger
tones that being out in the cold makes the organisation's voice ever more
necessary, but it is also likely to make the annual convention ever more of
a fringe event.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
