<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Pensions industry probes its future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Association of Pension Funds, the industry trade body, is to
fund an independent inquiry into long-term pension provision and has pledged
to publish its findings even if they could harm its members' interests.
Mr Ron Amy, association chairman, said it was making the unusual move
because 'there is a danger that vested interest and ideology will drive the
debate about pensions; the purpose is to make sure that the policy formation
process is well-informed.'
Mr Amy said the government's drive to promote personal pensions 'was about
making everybody into mini-capitalists,' and did not sufficiently consider
whether it was achieving better pension coverage for the lowest cost.
Mr Amy did not disclose the cost of the inquiry, which will be headed by Sir
John Anson, former second permanent secretary to the Treasury, who retired
in 1990.
Sir John said yesterday: 'Today's decisions on pensions policy will affect
those who retire in the first half of the next century. The purpose of the
inquiry is to consider whether changes need to be made to provide a stable
and affordable structure for pension provision in the long term which will
enable people to make informed choices with confidence.'
Among the inquiry board's members are Mr Andrew Dilnot, director of the
Institute for Fiscal Studies, which has recommended ending the provision
that allows for a tax-free lump sum to be available on retirement. The
association has strongly opposed this.
Also taking part are Mr Terry Banks, chief researcher on a report for the
Carnegie Institute on old age; Lady Wilcox, who chairs the National Consumer
Council; Mr John Harris, chairman of the Federation of Small Businesses; Mr
Roger Lyons, general secretary of the MSF general technical union; and Mr
Giovanni Tambur, co-ordinator of the European Commission Observation Network
of Occupational Pensions.
The review will consider the roles taken in the industry of the state,
employers and individuals.
Pension Fund Investment, separate section
</TEXT>
