<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Young hits at Europe 'obsession': IoD convention opens to
poor attendance; Regulation causes despair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY and STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British society is being divided by a futile obsession with Europe while its
industrial advantage evaporates, Lord Young warned the Institute of
Directors annual convention yesterday.
The IoD president said the European Union was wasting its time 'in
inward-looking arguments about lost causes' while the economies of Asia were
set to become larger than those of Europe and North America within six
years.
'By the millennium, the number of Asian households with an income of Dollars
30,000 or more will rise to 50m. How many homes in the UK have an income
that high? Perhaps 3m and not more than 4m. Out there is a fast-growing
market, perhaps 15 times greater than our own home market, for luxury and
quality goods.'
Yet the EU was 'fiddling whilst the Treaty of Rome burned', worrying over
causes such as single currencies and political union.
Mr Peter Morgan, IoD director-general, echoed Lord Young's sentiments in an
attack on the German social market and French economic nationalism. Mr
Morgan said Europe needed to change its wasteful regional, agricultural and
industrial policies radically if it was to meet the challenges of the
emerging markets.
Both speakers emphasised the need for de-regulation in Europe, but Lord
Young was particularly concerned over failure to remove trade barriers.
Reflecting the feeling among many of the Institute's members that Europe was
marginalising itself through over-regulation, Lord Young said the EU
intergovernmental conference in 1996 was 'probably our last chance to wake
up before the world passes us by'.
'It could take an axe to the institutions of the union and let in the spirit
of enterprise. It could make a bonfire of directives and give real meaning
to subsidiarity,' he said.
'Even the IMF has woken up to what we now have to do. Last week, they called
for the EU to reverse two decades of rising unemployment by reforming
employment protections, minimum wage laws, and unemployment insurance
schemes,' said Lord Young.
'We are now at a crossroads,' he said. With Asia emerging as the new centre
of gravity for commerce, it was 'high time' for British business to capture
markets.
Lord Young also appeared confident about the future of relations with Hong
Kong. 'I met the president of China less than two weeks ago and he told me
that nothing would affect business relationships with the UK,' he said.
</TEXT>
