<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Inflation pressures tamed, says CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Few signs of overheating or inflationary pressures in the UK economy appear
in the latest quarterly trends survey from the Confederation of British
Industry.
The proportion of companies working below capacity rose slightly to 59 per
cent this month from 57 per cent in January, while 92 per cent had
sufficient capacity to meet expected demand.
'The outlook for inflation remains positive, with no sign of cost and price
pressures emerging,' said Sir David Lees, chairman of the CBI's economic
affairs committee. The same number of companies reported that unit costs had
fallen during the past four months as reported an increase, and only a
balance of 2 percentage points expected a rise in costs over the next four
months.
A balance of 1 percentage point said domestic prices had fallen over the
past four months, and there was the same balance for companies expecting
prices to fall further over the next four months. The CBI calculates most of
its figures by subtracting the percentage of companies expecting a decline
in a variable from those reporting an increase, and by then expressing the
result as a balance.
The CBI also found that companies had been cutting their export prices. This
runs counter to official figures which appear to have shown that exporters
have been increasing prices. Mr Sudhir Junankar, associate director of
economic affairs, said the CBI was comfortable with its figures, which had
been prepared on a consistent basis - unlike the official trade figures
which recently introduced the Intra-stat system.
Figures for output and orders were positive, with the balance of 16
percentage points reporting higher total orders during the past four months
being the best figure since January 1989. 'As yet, there is no sign of
manufacturing output faltering in the face of the tax increases introduced
at the start of this month,' the CBI said. However, growth in output and
orders was at a slightly lower rate than had been expected when the sur-vey
was last conducted in January. British companies are making significant
progress towards world-class status, says a report out today, Graham Bowley
writes.
Researchers from the London Business School interviewed 21 manufacturing
companies including Shell UK, Rover Group and Courtaulds to find out if, and
how, British-based companies are striving to become world-class.
They found that all the companies they visited had achieved substantial
improvements over the past five years across a range of performance
indicators such as productivity and customer service.
Global Excellence, CBI, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford Street, London WC1A
1DU.
</TEXT>
