<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Howard criticises Lords on police bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard,the home secretary, last night called on the Commons to
overturn a key change made by the House of Lords to the controversial police
and magistrates' courts bill.
He accepted most of the amendments made when the government was defeated in
the Lords during sustained attacks on the bill, but insisted that their
refusal to accept new procedures for weeding out unsatisfactory police
officers could not be allowed to stand.
Mr Howard said the existing system did not allow police managers to review
an officer's behaviour and performance as a whole and this was 'totally
unacceptable'.
He also gave notice that MPs would be asked to reverse an amendment made by
the Lords which would prevent disciplinary proceedings being brought against
officers in respect of matters for which they had been tried and acquitted
in the criminal courts.
In a concession to the Lords Mr Howard said that police would continue to
have the right to be legally represented if they were at risk of dismissal,
forced resignation or facing a reduction in rank.
Mr Howard also bowed to the Lords in keeping the rank of chief inspector
while abolishing that of chief superintendent. This change was aimed at
securing a less top-heavy management structure.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's shadow home secretary, said the bill, although
'severely mauled' by the Lords, had not been changed nearly enough.
</TEXT>
