<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Taiwanese Airbus crash in Japan claims 261 lives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO, PAUL BETTS and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A China Airlines aircraft bound from Taipei in Taiwan to Nagoya in western
Japan crashed and exploded yesterday in Japan's second worst airline
disaster.
Officials said 261 people died and 10 survived when the Airbus A300-600R
plunged headlong into the grass to the right of the runway at Nagoya Airport
and burst into flames. Rescuers searching the charred wreckage took nine
hours to account for the last people missing after the accident.
Of the passengers, 158 were Japanese, 63 Taiwanese and 33 were of other
nationalities, officials said. The immediate cause of the disaster was not
known but airport control confirmed weather conditions were moderate and the
view clear at the time.
Witnesses said that the Airbus, whose wheels were not visible, approached
the airport's runway, then suddenly turned its nose upwards as if to take
off, before plunging within seconds almost at a 90-degree angle into the
ground. The aircraft was scattered into bits across several hundred metres
and the parts burst into a sea of flames which burned for 40 minutes as
rescue teams tried to free passengers trapped inside.
Airbus said last night three engineers had left for Nagoya. It declined to
comment on possible causes of the accident, but said it was the first
A300-600R to have crashed.
Japan's worst air disaster was on August 12 1985 when a Japan Air Lines
Boeing 747 crashed into a mountain north-east of Tokyo, killing 520.
</TEXT>
