<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Hata struggles to remake coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tsutomu Hata, Japan's recently elected prime minister, made no progress
yesterday in persuading the Social Democratic party to rejoin his crippled
coalition.
The deadlock threatens to prevent him forming a majority government, so
increasing the chance of an early general election. The opposition Liberal
Democratic party, encouraged by the break-up of the coalition, yesterday
called on Mr Hata to hand over power.
Mr Tomiichi Murayama, SDP chairman, refused to reply to Mr Hata's invitation
to discuss the socialists' decision early yesterday to leave the government
coalition, so removing its parliamentary majority.
The SDP, formerly the coalition's largest member, walked out in protest
against the formation of a new alliance, called Kaishin, by five
conservative groups led by Mr Hata's Japan Renewal party.
Only hours earlier, the SDP had cast a decisive vote for Mr Hata's prime
ministerial nomination in parliament. This was 'betrayal', said Mr Murayama.
The socialists had got the 'wrong impression', Mr Hata maintained.
Mr Hata should step down because he had lost the basis for his nomination as
leader, Mr Masaharu Gotoda, an LDP elder, said. 'Is it OK to entrust the
future of the people to such an insincere government?' asked Mr Yohei Kono,
LDP president.
Undeterred, Mr Hata said he planned to form a cabinet as soon as possible.
JRP officials say he needs to form a government by tomorrow at the latest.
The SDP has said it would co-operate with the government in passing a budget
for the current year. This has been blocked for more than a month by a
parliamentary row over former prime minister Morihiro Hosokawa's financial
propriety, then by the coalition policy row following Mr Hosokawa's
resignation. The government is ticking over on a provisional budget, which
expires on May 20.
The socialists have also offered to co-operate on economic pump-priming
measures, but will not support tax reforms, the most important piece of
legislation facing the new government.
The socialists' departure was 'only natural', the Asahi Shimbun newspaper
said yesterday. The party had been out of line with its former partners on
most issues, ever since the coalition was formed last July after the LDP's
first election defeat in 38 years.
The Asahi and other newspapers questioned Mr Hata's ability to exert strong
leadership and suggested the formation of Kaishin showed the increased
behind-the-scenes influence of Mr Ichiro Ozawa, the government's backroom
strategist. Mr Ozawa was virtual 'owner' of the Hata administration, the
Nihon Keizai Shimbun financial daily said.
</TEXT>
