<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Venezuela bank chief quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Ruth de Krivoy, president of Venezuela's central bank, resigned last
night after facing heavy pressure from the government of President Rafael
Caldera to change the bank's monetary policy and force reductions in
interest rates.
Mr Omar Bello, the first vice-president at the central bank, will
temporarily replace Mrs de Krivoy, who is an internationally respected
economist. She was viewed as playing an important stabilising role in
Venezuela's public sector.
Mrs de Krivoy's resignation represents a serious blow to the image of the
Caldera government, which began a five-year term in February. Beset by
economic and financial problems, the Caldera administration has developed
policies aimed at placing it in the middle ground between free market
economics and heavy government intervention.
As part of this programme, the government recently began pressing the
central bank to force domestic interest rates downward even though inflation
remains high. Mrs de Krivoy apparently rejected these pressures, saying in
her letter of resignation that she could not carry out policies that
violated economic principles.
Mrs De Krivoy insisted on the need to maintain a tight policy to stop
speculation in the money markets, to fight inflation and to protect foreign
reserves that have fallen because of a banking crisis.
Authorities have spent about Dollars 5.9bn - the equivalent of half the 1994
budget - to support banks. About Dollars 2.7bn was spent to bail out Banco
Latino, previously Venezuela's second biggest bank, which was taken over by
the government after failing to meet financial commitments.
</TEXT>
