<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Stable currencies put on IMF agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Continental European finance ministers have put greater exchange rate
stability back on the international monetary agenda.
But any idea of creating a new world monetary system or extending Europe's
experience with the exchange rate mechanism to other countries stands
virtually no chance of acceptance by the biggest industrial nations.
Following the meeting this week of the policy-making interim committee of
the International Monetary Fund, Mr Philippe Maystadt, Belgian finance
minister and committee chairman, disclosed that the Fund's executive board
had been asked to study 'possible ways to introduce a greater degree of
discipline in the present exchange rate system'.
The Fund board was asked to report back to the committee by its next meeting
in Madrid in October.
Mr Michel Camdessus, IMF managing director, made clear he believed there was
little chance of a new system to stabilise exchange rates and that the
problem was better addressed through strengthened co-ordination of economic
policies.
</TEXT>
