<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / EMI chief drops ERM line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alexandre Lamfalussy, president of the European Monetary Institute,
yesterday joined a growing consensus in Europe that the path to a single
currency no longer lies via a resurrection of the old exchange rate
mechanism. In testimony to the European parliament, Mr Lamfalussy said he
had changed his mind about the need to revive the ERM's narrow fluctuation
bands. Currency stability was the fundamental objective, he said. Mr
Lamfalussy expressed cautious optimism about exchange rate stability,
tempered by a warning to member states to reduce their record budget
deficits. Failure to do so risked an increase in long-term rates, which
could choke off the incipient recovery in Europe.
Mr Lamfalussy's remarks on the future of the ERM reflect a new consensus
among central bankers, the European Commission and the Bundesbank that the
15 per cent fluctuation bands - introduced as a crisis measure last August -
have helped not only to deter speculators but also to reinforce currency
stability. The EMI president said he favoured keeping the wide bands for as
long as possible. The unexpected success of the crisis measures still leaves
ministers with a dilemma: how to reconcile the 15 per cent bands with the
Maastricht treaty's provision that a currency must be a member of the
'normal' ERM bands for two years to qualify to join a future single
currency.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
</CN>
