<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Big powers promise a united front on Bosnia: Diplomats plan
to restrict Serbs to 49% of republic as fears grow of renewed fighting in
north-east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The newly established four-power 'contact group' on Bosnia promised
yesterday to present a united front as they apply pressure on both Bosnian
Serbs and Moslems to agree a negotiated settlement.
The group - comprising Russia, the US, the United Nations and the European
Union - resolved at its first meeting in London to avoid the splits between
the west and Russia which have dogged attempts to secure an accord between
Moslems and Serbs.
The group's representatives - aiming to capitalise on an apparent easing of
tension as the Serbs withdraw from the enclave of Gorazde under threat of
air strikes - hope to travel to Sarajevo tomorrow. They will then visit
Pale, the Bosnian Serb headquarters.
The group's plans were announced by Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary
of state, in Geneva after a meeting with Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian
foreign minister.
In a gesture of western keenness to include Russia in the peace process, Mr
Christopher took Mr Vitaly Churkin, Moscow's chief negotiator in former
Yugoslavia, with him when he flew from London to Geneva on his US Air Force
jet.
The contact group hopes to revive a peace plan under which the Serbs would
limit their share of Bosnian territory to 49 per cent - they hold 70 per
cent now - while the remaining territory would be occupied by the new
Croat-Moslem federation.
Mr Yasushi Akashi, head of UN operations in former Yugoslavia, said early
today that Bosnian Serbs had effectively complied with a Nato ultimatum to
withdraw their heavy weapons from within the 20km (12 miles) exclusion zone
around Gorazde. As a result, there was no need for immediate air strikes.
'On the basis of information available right now, and subject to further
verification, I have come to the conclusion there is no need to ask Nato for
air strikes at this time,' he told reporters in Zagreb.
Bosnian radio yesterday accused Serb forces of shelling Moslem positions
near the north-eastern town of Brcko, at the narrowest point of the corridor
linking Serbia to Serb-held Bosnia and Croatia.
Serb media meanwhile accused the Bosnian Moslem army of planning an imminent
offensive in northern Bosnia.
The exchange of allegations follows reports from witnesses that the Bosnian
Serbs are preparing to launch an offensive in that area, and charges that
Croat forces have been massing to the north.
Preservation of the self-styled 'Serb Republic' in Bosnia depends on
main-taining the land corridor.
There were reports from Serb sources, confirmed by some independent
observers, that Moslem forces had violated the ceasefire in Gorazde by
trying to trap a Serb unit within the enclave so it would become a target
for Nato airstrikes when the ultimatum expired today.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    YUZ  Yugoslavia, East Europe.
    BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
