<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 94 / Lubbers leaves heirs and rivals a hard act to follow: Dutch
national elections expose the vulnerability of political aspirants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ruud Lubbers is a hard act to follow, as his rivals and political heirs
in the Netherlands are ruefully discovering in the run-up to national
elections on May 3.
Mr Lubbers, 54, the longest-serving prime minister in Dutch history, is
leaving national politics after three consecutive terms in office. His
departure is a serious blow to his Christian Democrat party (CDA), which
traditionally dominates Dutch politics but which is now struggling in the
polls.
When the Lubbers era began in 1982, the country's crippling public debt, its
rigid labour market and its dual problems of inflation and unemployment had
spawned the pejorative term 'Hollanditis.' But as he prepares to leave
office, possibly to fight for the presidency of the European Commission in
Brussels, Mr Lubbers leaves behind a surprisingly muscular economy.
In the early 1980s, his 'no-nonsense' approach and radical (by Dutch
standards) cuts in social benefits earned him the nickname 'Ruud Shock'
abroad, making him one of the few Dutch prime ministers whose name is known
to foreigners.
Mr Lubbers exploited the recession of the early 1980s to cut the pay of
civil servants and scale back unemployment and disability benefits. In his
12 years in office, he also cut the budget deficit from 10.1 per cent of net
national income to 3.8 per cent, although the absolute level of public debt
has continued to rise.
In normal times, Mr Lubbers' anointment of Mr Elco Brinkman as his successor
as party leader would have been enough to ensure that Mr Brinkman would also
succeed him as prime minister. The CDA has had a place in every government
coalition since the second world war, and it usually provides the prime
minister. This year, however, the Dutch electoral race is wide open, and the
CDA's support is crumbling.
Part of the problem is the transition from a popular, well-tried politician
in Mr Lubbers to Mr Brinkman, who has led the CDA in the lower house of
parliament for the past four years.
Mr Lubbers has clearly become an institution. In a recent newspaper
interview he admitted: 'There are whole generations of people who think only
of Ruud Lubbers when they hear the word prime minister. Younger voters have
experienced only me. From a democratic perspective, it's good to turn this
page.'
But the handover to Mr Brinkman has been messy, culminating in signs of
disagreement and friction between the two men. Mr Lubbers first signalled
his preference for Mr Brinkman after the CDA's last electoral victory in
1989, putting his successor in the uncomfortable and visible role of 'heir
apparent' for nearly five years.
Matters were not helped by the presentation of the CDA platform in January,
when plans to freeze old age pension payments sparked a storm of protest.
The chairman of the CDA, Mr Wim van Velzen, resigned to take the blame but
much of the fault was apportioned to Mr Brinkman.
Then, in early April, it emerged that Mr Brinkman held a non-executive
directorship at a company linked to his wife's uncle who was known to have
had run-ins with the tax authorities. The episode has dominated news
reporting in the crucial weeks before the elections.
Mr Brinkman can draw some comfort from the fact that Mr Lubbers, too, began
his tenure as premier facing low popularity and high scepticism, both inside
and outside the party.
The two men share other similarities. . Although Mr Lubbers is a
Jesuit-educated Catholic while Mr Brinkman grew up in a conservative
Calvinist area east of Rotterdam, both men were high-fliers who attained
national office early.
Mr Lubbers, scion of a rich Rotterdam industrialist, was minister of
economic affairs when he was just 34 and became prime minister at 43, the
youngest in Dutch history.
Mr Brinkman, son of a small-town mayor, became minister of culture and
health at the age of 34. Now aged 46, he has a stiff and forbidding image
that belies his youth.
Both men launched their bids for the prime minister's job from their
positions as leader of the CDA in parliament. But the truth now is that the
outlook for the CDA is so grim that the unthinkable may happen: the
Netherlands' 'party of government' could be transformed into a party of
opposition.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NLZ  Netherlands, EC.
</CN>
