<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (28): Hankering after the old
days - Zipperhead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mainframe computing specialists are wasting their time if they apply for
jobs at the London International Financial Futures Exchange. For Liffe only
wants young people with personal computing and Unix experience and its
advertisements spell out that mainframe people are unlikely to fit the bill.
Liffe says such people tend to have expertise in specific technical areas,
whereas today's computing person needs an open attitude and greater
adaptability.
Such views among organisations moving to networked personal computers and
office systems have led to the emergence of the term 'zipperhead.' The
research company Xephon, in its annual handbook of IBM terminology, defines
a zipperhead as 'someone with a closed mind, typically a middle-aged person
who remembers the days when you could carry a mainframe operating system
around as a deck of punched cards - and wishes you still could'.
Job prospects for dyed-in-the-wool zipperheads are certainly falling. The
National Computing Centre's annual survey shows that programmers now make up
14 per cent of systems staff, compared with 34 per cent six years ago. The
demand now is for end-user support people, who have come from nowhere in
four years, to account for 13 per cent.
In addition there will be just four per cent growth in demand for
programmers over the next five years - compared with more than 30 per cent
for end-user support people and 40 per cent for network staff.
These findings are underlined by annual counts of job advertisements by
Salary Survey Publications for trade journal Computer Weekly. These show
that skills in local area networking and in desk-top computing products such
as Windows, Oracle and Ingres have moved into the top 10 skills in most
demand in the last three years at the expense of expertise in specialist
mainframe products.
Older people (in computing anyone over 35 seems to be seen as old) tend to
have the traditional mainframe skills. Indeed, age has a role in the
zipperhead debate. Older people might have had PCs thrust upon them, the
argument goes, but young people have grown up with them. And if the average
age of the PC or client-server team is 25 and even the manager is only 30,
how can a 45-year-old fit in?
All these issues are summed up by Mr Ian Maclachlan, professional services
director at client-server systems specialist RCMS, which has helped
companies like Bass and rank Xerox move to client-server systems.
'Mainframe staff are used to long development cycles; get heavily involved
at systems level; are programmers of logic; do not believe client-server
technology can replace the functionality and performance of legacy systems;
and understand and appreciate rigorous development methods for big
applications,' he says.
'PC staff are used to short development cycles; only work at application
level; understand personal productivity tools; expect high recognition for
their work; and have no disciplined approach to development.'
However, Mr Maclachlan's contrasting lists show room for beneficial
compromise. For example professional management of computing projects has
become a key topic in the last 18 months following government and other
reports highlighting poor quality. A national examination has been
introduced by the British Computer Society's Information Systems
Examinations Board.
The fact that traditional mainframe people have been brought up with
disciplined approaches to development is one reason why recruitment agency
Neville John Associates, in Chester, has launched a contract computing
service based on older people. As the company says, older people have seen
it all. Far from being stuck in the past, they have been through change many
times as technology has moved forward. They can bring experience, realism
and a cautious restraining hand to organisations which might be tempted to
rush for the latest over-hyped 'new' product or approach.
Research into staffing needs by the Institute of Data Processing Management
and the Women into Information Technology campaign concludes that
organisations should 'retread' existing people 'instead of replacing them by
cheaper or supposedly flexible youngsters.'
The learning curve of the latter group can be expensive, the research report
says. It adds that 'retreading should include business, marketing,
management and personal communication skills training' to enable computing
specialists to work more effectively with end-users, especially managers.
Neville John Associates and others point to another role for experienced
older people. Although today's talk is all about PCs and client-servers
systems, many important corporate systems run on mainframes. Most programs
are still written in the long-established Cobol language and there are many
in the esoteric Assembler machine language and in PL/I, dating back 12-15
years yet well proven and in daily use. Maintenance of such programs is just
the job for diehard zipperheads.
Age has long been an issue in employment and various organisations have
lobbied for years to get age discrimination outlawed, just as sex and race
discrimination are.
The arguments will probably go on forever - unlike the people involved in
them. For today's bright young thing is inevitably tomorrow's zipperhead.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
