<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (26): The last word on Unix -
X/Open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The definition of an Open System has always been open to question. Dr
Johnson, were he still labouring over his dictionary, would have to turn to
the body called X/Open for the definitive description.
X/Open, the new owner of the name Unix, has a definition that would
overshadow Johnson's own life work; 24 volumes weighing half a hundredweight
(unless delivered on compact disk).
Most associate 'openness' with Unix, the operating system adopted in the
1980s by so many minicomputer vendors that it overcame the proprietary
interests of any one, including IBM.
Ten years ago, not everyone was convinced that this committee-inspired camel
with unconventional pedigree would win out over their sleek proprietary
horses. Many backed both, just in case. But in a decade, Unix has become the
undisputed mid-range standard, which has changed the face, and more
prosaically the pricing structure, of computing.
X/Open - a collaboration of interested parties, yet also an authority over
all of them - has the job of moving the industry towards a single, unified
specification for the Unix operating system. As in religion and politics,
the most bitter fighting has been internal.
According to Geoff Morris, president of X/Open and the high priest of open
systems, there is only one way ahead and it is open.
'The world's major businesses report their external spending on open systems
will dominate 58 per cent of the world market by 1996,' he said. Mr Morris
has more detail to back up this claim. It comes from X/Open's annual market
research, called Xtra, and more than 80 IT user organisations serving on
X/Open's user council.
VESTED INTERESTS
There have been a confusing number of organisations campaigning for various
Unix causes, mostly driven by allied vendors with a vested interest. But the
Open Systems Foundation (OS/F), the defunct Unix International, and even the
Common Open Software Environment (Cose), have all been more concerned with
vendor-issues than user-led issues. X/Open works with OS/F, (whose work will
now reference X/Open's Xtra requirement process) as well as through a number
of committees and other associations such as the Object Management Group and
the Network Management Forum.
The real change for X/Open is more to do with users than vendors. Users, at
last, are demanding a place in the forum and some input into the
decision-making, especially in committee. This is perhaps the least
perceptible development, but the most significant and promising long-term
one, because 'open' is not just about new systems, and not just about Unix.
Mr Morris said, 'X/Open has suffered from being dependent on the vendor-led
community but by 1993 only half its income came from vendors, and by 1995,
it will be less than a quarter.'
Richard Jaross is director of Uniforum, an organisation set up to represent
the many different bodies with an interest in open systems. He is among
those seeking to broaden the definition - 'an open system makes it possible
for users to run their applications seamlessly across computer platforms, no
matter who wrote the underlying systems software, or who made the computing
hardware,' he said.
The market has caught up with this idea because, as Xtra confirmed, users
now put 'openness' high on the list for new systems. The spread of
client-server systems, usually with Unix-based systems at the centre, is
part of the user-led drive to downsize. But power on the desktop is more
useful if it can interface with other systems.
LONG-AWAITED MOMENT
Symbolically, in October 1993, X/Open became the owner of the name Unix.
Novell, which acquired the Unix system last year, granted its trademark
rights to X/Open for use as one of its standard brands. This marked a moment
that many Unix proponents had long hoped for, when no single vendor would
own Unix.
In September last year came the technical embodiment of this aim: Spec 1170.
This is the single specification devised to replace existing incompatible
versions after 1994, to which all products using the name Unix must comply.
The 1170 tag itself, was a reminder of how far Unix had come since it was
discovered by a generation of students doing their own thing on DEC
PDP-11/70s.
Spec 1170 is the blend between a single and a multiple Unix, which allows
individual suppliers to add extras to their products to improve performance
and functions, just as they always have.
'The events of the last year have forced the hand of Unix vendors, bringing
a more practical slant to the Unix debate,' said Mark Kusionowicz, manager
of systems product marketing in the server systems division of UK systems
supplier ICL. 'In effect, the unwelcome advance of NT has had a positive
influence on the supplier industry.'
According to an end user, Rob Winterbourne, the Unix systems support team
manager at Barclays Computer Operations, the issue of 'Unices' is less
relevant as the movement advances.
'The major benefits are in the portability of applications,' he said. 'To us
as a business, the formalisation of 'middleware' and the ability to put
pressure on suppliers is important. For Joe Developer, it shouldn't matter
if he's working on an IBM RS/6000, an HP9000 or a DEC Alpha. Spec1170 is an
indication that X/Open, while still dominated by suppliers, really is
bending towards users.'
X/Open's latest initiative is to address a marketplace not even dreamed of
when Unix was used on teletype terminals: the information highways leading
to the desktop (see D for Desktop Video). The X/Open Desktop Working Group
will address the co-existence of many different environments on one screen.
X/Open specified products will be tested - the tricky bit - and 'branded.'
Unix is the key to most Open Systems solutions and it is that rare
phenomenon in the computer industry - a standard reached by consensus. This
consensus was not achieved without casualties but the whole idea was that
some people would have to give up their own idiosyncratic interpretations of
Unix in the cause of standards.
X/Open has survived and flourished in spite of the various Unix sects, by
concentrating on deliverables like the Application Programming Interfaces
specified in 1170. Along with the most successful collaborations in the
motor industry, the pooled resources should result in developments for the
common good.
'X/Open has customers,' Mr Morris said. 'It can demonstrate where it adds
value. A few years ago, no one would have thought that of a standards
organisation.'
X/Open was set up in 1984 to oversee the technical nitty-gritty of
specifying an applications environment for Unix. Its mission statement
(aptly named given the religious fervour of its proponents), was 'to bring
greater value to users through the practical implementation of open
systems'.
Ten years ago, not everyone was convinced Unix would work, let alone X/Open.
The organisation carried all the hopes and fears of the Unix community.
Early commentators thought it a well-meaning cause doomed by political
in-fighting. To succeed it had to persuade its constituents, the suppliers,
to abandon some of the very things they had done to make Unix a more
appealing option on their particular hardware.
FRAGMENTATION
X/Open, the aim of which was to eliminate industry fragmentation, stayed
dignified throughout the so-called 'Unix wars' in which vendors aligned
themselves under separate banners, bickering over such standards as
graphical user interfaces.
Unix itself had unpromising antecedents for a universal operating system. It
was owned, not by the giant IBM but by AT&amp;T, the US telecommunications
group, which in the late 1970s was not allowed to compete in the computer
market. This resulted in text peppered with the famous trade mark, 'Unix is
a trademark of Bell Laboratories', and the farcical situation that anyone
wanting to provide Unix had to license it, debug it and badge it by some
other name - inevitably, one with an X in it.
Unix represented an opportunity for the rest of the Bunch (the term used to
describe the also-rans who competed with IBM) to create a common platform on
which applications would be portable.
</TEXT>
<XX>
