<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (21): The golden age is yet to
dawn - Software Engineering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Software builders have tried to apply engineering disciplines to software
production for more than a quarter of a century with the hope that one day
software can be produced as easily as automobiles.
But only recently - with the advent of new techniques such as
object-oriented design - has some progress has been made outside a few
specialist areas.
Software for use in 'life-or-death' applications such as aerospace and
defence has made most use of the engineering approach using standard
components and production engineering processes.
The large development budgets available to build these systems make it
possible to use expensive procedures to control the design and development
of software. Such development methods emphasise meticulous early design,
tight project control and the use of tried and tested 'components'.
Commercial software production - with its tighter delivery schedules and
limited budgets - has not, so far, been able to take much advantage of
engineering techniques. Despite attempts to introduce computer-aided
software engineering (CASE) development methods, commercial software
production remains more a craft than an engineering discipline.
This looks set to change in the next few years.
The main drive towards the engineering approach has come from
object-oriented computing, which is now widely accepted as the most
important future direction for software design.
The use of standard 'parts' or 'components' is a key concept in
object-oriented design. In the same way that a motor car manufacturer buys
in parts such as gear boxes and engines, the object-oriented software
developer builds systems from proven software components.
Most software tool developers are using object-oriented (O-O) techniques to
reinforce the engineering approach: 'Object-oriented computing is now
showing promise because it can deal with repeatable development processes.
It has reached a level of maturity where components can be re-used and,
slowly, the dream of software engineering is being realised,' says Mr Don
Kavanagh, European consultancy manager from software tool developer
Interactive Data Environments (IDE).
'But it goes well beyond simple code re-use. Objects let you re-use
high-level concepts too. You can build high-level enterprise objects which
are like engineering blueprints.'
He adds that applications of the future will be built like Lego models -
which will make it easier for non-programmers to engineer their own
applications from kits of parts. This has profound implications for the
software industry - 'the structure of the software industry is changing in a
way which poses a threat to traditional assembly line programming,' says Mr
Dave Thomas, founder and chief executive of Object Technology International,
which specialises in O-O software tools - 'we are seeing a move to creating
high-level user objects which are business specific. Banks like Morgan
Stanley and Credit Suisse are building object-oriented financial options
'components' which they could publish for general use,' says Mr Thomas.
This trend has been highlighted recently with the foundation of the Business
Object Management Special Interest Group (Bomsig), which aims to create
applications objects for specific industries.
There are certain processes which all companies in an industrial sector use.
In the past, they have each developed their own expensive software to deal
with such issues as industry standards and government legislation. Bomsig
participants hope to create standard 'parts' appropriate to particular
industries which all companies can license.
NO EASY ANSWERS
But this will not be without its problems. Dr Robert Rockwell, chief
technology adviser at German software engineering specialist Softlab
suggests that the origins of O-O design place a question mark over the long
term success of the engineering approach: 'The concept of engineering
software is one of the Holy Grails of the software industry. But there is a
large class of software which can't be produced in this way,' he says.
'Engineering is about standard parts and standard procedures. Objects
certainly give you standard parts - but their background runs counter to
standard procedures.'
Dr Rockwell says object technology comes from institutions with flat
hierarchies with no bosses and no standard procedures - such as universities
and research laboratories. This puts it in direct conflict with the
traditional business approaches to building software - where procedures are
imposed from the top.
The main problem with software is, of course, that it is unlike any other
human artefact. Analogies with other production processes while useful are,
therefore, bound to be inadequate. This makes software production hard to
define formally and, ultimately, difficult to 'engineer.' There is no doubt
that the object-oriented approach is a step forward. It will help to
reinforce a more disciplined approach to creating applications software
through use of tried-and-tested components.
Whether it will lead to a golden age of genuine software engineering,
however, remains unclear.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
