</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (22): Software star of the
Olympics - Transaction Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the stars at this year's Winter Olympic Games in Lillehammer, Norway,
was, according to IBM, a 25-year-old software package.
Known by the initials CICS, this veteran program was responsible for
managing the results and information network installed at the games.
The journalists and commentators in Lillehammer were unaware that they were
CICS 'users' as the intricacies of the technology were hidden by a
user-friendly graphical user interfaces (GUIs - with their pull-down menus,
icons and overlapping windows). But they joined millions of people around
the world who, unknowingly, rely on CICS software every day.
You probably are a CICS user yourself. Many of the automatic teller machines
(ATM) operated by banks and building societies are controlled by CICS and
most large companies use it.
CICS - an acronym for for Customer Information Control System - is the most
successful example of a transaction processing (TP) monitor. It addresses a
persistent problem in computing: how to share a single resource among many
users.
Typically, TP monitors like CICS are used to control access to important
data and ensure it does not become corrupt.
In a banking system a TP monitor controls access from ATMs to individual
accounts. The standard procedure involves entering a magnetic stripe card
into the machine's reader, typing in a personal identification number (PIN)
and requesting a service, such as cash withdrawal or balance statement.
The ATM sends a series of messages to a central computer, where the account
details are checked. If the user is authorised, a message is sent back to
the ATM to carry out the customer's request. With all of these messages
moving around the network, it is easy to imagine that an important one might
get lost. This is where the TP monitor comes in, by ensuring that messages
get to the right destination and that appropriate data files are updated. It
also synchronises changes to data and makes sure that users do not have to
wait too long for a response.
As the longevity of CICS illustrates, TP monitors are well-established in
large-scale mainframe data processing. PC networks, however, do not as yet
have mechanisms like this. But with a move to client-server computing, (see
page four), they are being expected to provide the security and the
resilience to equal mainframes and minicomputers.
A COMPLEX TASK
Controlling communication traffic between many computers and environments
attached to a network is a complex task at any level. But the software
structures needed to make an open network of personal computers and servers
match the mainframe for performance and reliability are only now beginning
to find their way on to the PC agenda.
The root of the problem lies in how business transactions are processed.
These involve far more than passing an 'e-mail' message or a request for
data to a server - functions which a PC network can perform adequately
enough. Processing business transactions demands a solid foundation of
management software to make sure that it is properly controlled.
When, for example, a company receives an order, a whole sequence of
processes is set in motion. The customer's credit is checked, the ledger is
updated, stock counts are reduced and so on. Some of these processes follow
each other and others can happen in parallel. Above all, they must be
controlled and managed - or orders may be lost or duplicated.
If the order processing application is distributed across a client/server
network, a high-level, transaction 'manager' - a sort of 'super' TP monitor
 -is essential.
There are a number of possible candidates for this role. Conventional TP
monitors are being extended from their proprietary base to cope with 'open'
client-server systems and IBM has extended CICS to all of its main hardware
platforms and operating environments - in addition to licensing it to other
manufacturers. Novell is developing the Tuxedo monitor, which it inherited
from its takeover of Unix Systems Laboratories, to compete with CICS in
client-server systems.
Database software developers are also building transaction management
features into their database products. Oracle, Ingres, Sybase and Informix
all offer some level of transaction management as part of their products.
Emerging standards in object-oriented computing (see software engineering,
this page) also include transaction management features.
It seems likely that the problem of managing transactions in an open
client-server environment will be solved by a combination of one or more of
these approaches. What is clear, however, is that it is a problem which will
continue to grow and demand the attention of software developers across
every aspect of modern computing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
