<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (19): A help in reducing the
risks - Quality Programmes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British Standards Institute (BSI) has a lot to answer for. When BS5750
was introduced as a national standard for quality management systems in 1979
it launched a whole raft of management trends, with associated jargon.
Attaining BS5750 became a significant totem in the burgeoning religion of
Total Quality Management (TQM). Quality itself is no bad thing but BS5750
certification appears to generate enthusiasm for the number as much as the
ethos it represents.
Mark Churchward is an Oxford-based independent technology consultant who
greets the rise of the quality culture: 'I've been an evangelist for
quality. BS5750 is a bit like a creed. When you say you're going to do
things a certain way, you have to do it that way.'
But he concedes that getting a quality stamp is no panacea - 'there isn't
any inherent yardstick which ensures that staff work towards a better
quality company.' In other words, without a tool to measure your quality
process, the whole affair degenerates into yet another exercise in nebulous
management jargon.
A company applies for BSI accreditation. The BSI or an approved outside body
works with the applicant to ensure that its quality principles are applied
rigorously across the board. Registration, costing upwards of Pounds 990
(for the smallest firm) is then awarded, after which the company can expect
at least two booked inspections a year from the BSI or the outside body. So
measurement is an extremely practical step; it keeps the inspectors happy.
Can software meet this need for measurement? Ajay Sood was advising on
technology requirements at Peterhead Polytechnic when he realised 'that
quality assessment management had problems.' Sood believed that BS5750 was
'becoming a paper exercise.' His answer was to defect from academe and enter
the commercial fray with a Peterhead colleague. Their company, Orchid, is a
small software house based in Newcastle-upon-Tyne dedicated to writing
programs that put BS5750 into practice.
Orchid was launched on the back of thorough research: 'We picked the top 200
companies in the north-east and booked an hour to talk with the quality
managers.'
Apparently these people feel themselves to be a neglected and misunderstood
species and Sood's survey offered them some much appreciated therapy. It
emerged that quality managers are finding the much-vaunted quality standard
a bit of a bind.
Over 84 per cent of the quality managers questioned described themselves as
'computer novices,' although the vast majority used some form of computer
records. But the reports generated from quality management activity varied
from site to site. Without a fixed format the national standard was being
monitored in an imprecise way.
'The trouble with BS5750 is that it really is one big headache in terms of
paper,' says Sood. Not that this deters the rush to quality certification -
'there are companies going for it for its own sake.'
Orchid's balm for the hard-pressed and isolated quality manager is a progam
called Computerised Quality Management (CQM). Written for the IBM-PC and
costing between Pounds 750 and Pounds 7,000, CQM controls the documentation
spawned by BS5750. CQM lists the staff responsible for quality assurance and
assigns relevant documents to them. It sets up an internal audit trail that
allows the quality manager to review procedures, note achievements and
isolate failures of quality.
Among practical benefits claimed by Orchid is a diary generated
automatically by CQM to outline the quality manager's future activities in
any given week.
Dunlop Hydraulic Hose at Gateshead is a CQM site. Quality assurance manager
Alan Donnelly points out that BS5750 amounts to a good operating procedure
'that you'd expect to find in any successful company.' But a dedicated
quality program formalises his task. That in turn keeps BSI certification on
board. CQM proves to the inspectors that the job is being done.
Software development is a notoriously risky business. Projects fall
hopelessly behind schedule and run over budget. Praxis is a Bath-based
software house set up in 1983. Chairman Martyn Thomas has always felt that
software could benefit from a strict regime of quality control. Praxis
achieved BS5750 registration in 1986.
According to Mr Thomas, this meant much more than another certificate to
hang on the boardroom wall - 'we put in place a quality management system
that has saved us a huge amount of money. We have standards for notation,
how plans are signed off, who has final approval. The whole principle is
that we think about how to assure quality to begin with.'
Praxis feels confident bidding for fixed-price contracts - 'the running
costs of quality assurance add no more than 1 per cent to the cost of a
project. But it takes the risk out of the system. Our average variance from
cost estimates is 10 per cent. Before we started to apply quality management
it was 20 per cent.'
For Praxis, quality means knowing a contract will bring home a profit.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P7372 Prepackaged Software.
    P7376 Computer Facilities Management.
</IN>
<XX>
