<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (18): Giants line up for a battle
royal - Power PC/Pentium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BANKS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Though it would be easy to consider the competition between Complex
Instruction Set Computer (CISC) processors and Reduced Instruction Set
Computer (RISC) processors as a straight fight for world supremacy between
Intel's x86 family and the IBM/Motorola/Apple PowerPC, the situation is not
quite that simple.
There are other factors in the equation, such as what happens in the world
of operating systems and workstations. But a battle royal does seem likely.
For the first time in 12 years Intel's dominance of desktop and personal
computing processors has been threatened. Its designs are tied to a
pantechnicon of baggage from its past successes. Every new design has to
make sure that applications written five or even 10 years ago can run in the
new environment.
RISC processors, on the other hand, have been specifically designed to run a
set of instructions that have been optimised to meet the needs of desktop
applications. As such, they are ready to take on the demands of new
operating systems and new applications requirements like multimedia,
communications and complex, rich document structures. They also have enough
power to emulate the 'old world' of the PC, if those applications are needed
in the newer environments, while leaving much of the baggage behind.
Intel's response to RISC processors came a year ago with the launch of the
Pentium, but the circuit is big, hot and offers only marginal performance
improvements over the 486 processor. It's also still expensive, costing
around Dollars 700 each in lots of 1,000.
Although the Pentium is still in production, this year it has had a
significant redesign which reduces the chip size by 45 per cent, reduces the
voltage required from 5V to 3.3V, and reduces the design geometries from 0.8
micron to 0.6 micron. Most important of all, the clock speed goes up from
66MHz to 90MHz, with 100MHz available in limited quantities.
Known as the P54C, this solves many of the problems with the earlier device,
nearly doubling performance on industry-accepted benchmarks. It also reduces
heat dissipation, making it much more amenable to use.
The PowerPC, designed by IBM, Motorola and Apple, is by far the strongest
rival Intel has had to face. The first processor, the PowerPC 601, has
recently been upgraded from 66MHz to 100MHz and its performance is ahead of
the P54C. Its price is down to Dollars 238 each in lots of 20,000.
The alliance has a range of other processors in the family, including the
603 for low-end, low-power consumption applications and the 620 for high-end
workstations.
PowerPC is such a strong contender because it is the first RISC processor to
be manufactured by a merchant-market semiconductor producer, Motorola. While
Motorola makes only the component, all other RISC processors are
manufactured as part of a larger business model - where they are an integral
part of, and so funded by, the sale of complete workstations.
Motorola's processor families, the 68xxx and 81xxx, have either been beaten
in the market by Intel or other RISC processor suppliers. The company
therefore has a strong vested interest in seeing PowerPC succeed and is
prepared to use the tighter margins and aggressive marketing common in the
semiconductor industry.
The workstation market itself is changing. Workstations are usually
powerful, expensive, specialist systems, but the arrival of Pentium means
that a typical PC can now provide similar performance at far more aggressive
price points.
Perhaps the most important question, however, is in software. Intel and
PowerPC can, or will be able to, run the leading operating systems for the
forseeable future, such as Microsoft's WindowsNT, Unix (especially the
unified X/Open variety), OS/2 and the WorkPlace OS coming later this year.
PowerPC's advantage in the field of software is that it can also run Apple
Macintosh applications. Though often sidelined as a niche product, the
Macintosh accounts for about 15 per cent of the desktop market and has a
number of applications, especially in areas such as multimedia, crying out
for higher performance hardware. Intel is unlikely to take this threat lying
down. It has the resources to be aggressive in the market and is bound to
respond. But as Compaq Computer's announcement in February - that it is
seriously considering using PowerPC - demonstrates, for the first time Intel
has a real fight on its hands.
</TEXT>
