<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (14): No longer a Cinderella
sector - Mass storage devices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BANKS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mass storage has always been something of a poor relation to other, higher
profile forms of information technology, but the arrival of the CD-Rom
(compact optical disk with a read-only memory) has improved its status.
Now, with the advent of multimedia - the latest technology which
incorporates text, graphics, sound and video - the CD Rom is set to come
into its own. Multimedia needs huge quantities of fast, cheap mass storage,
something CD Rom can provide.
The CD-Rom combines a high capacity for data storage with reasonable (and
improving) data retrieval times, reasonable writing speed and a cheap
platform for publishable data.
Compact disc technology is now well known through the wide use of the
laser-based CD players found in most hi-fi systems, which use the same basic
digital data storage system. Two of the three types of CD-ROMs will affect
the development of multimedia.
The first is the read-only CD-Rom. This is an increasingly popular form for
applications for both consumer and business to business users.
Those applications can include general business packages, such as word
processing, spreadsheet and databases. Here CD-Roms are far more
cost-effective and convenient than floppy disks. One CD-Rom has space for
several programs, whereas anything up to 20 floppy disks may be needed to
carry instructions for one program.
Program installation is therefore easier, and the disks have enough space to
provide demonstrations of other programs so users can experiment. If they
decide to buy the application, the supplier will give them the information
to unlock the rest of the program.
CD-Roms are also useful for publishing databases and companies such as
Microsoft have not been slow to see the information and education
possibilities. Encyclopedias, reference works and art collections are just
three areas now available on database.
The second CD-Rom to affect multimedia is the magneto-optical rewritable
disk. This is similar to the magnetic floppy and hard disk, as data can be
written and rewritten on it. Its advantages are again a high capacity and
low cost but its slow writing and reading speeds compare unfavourably with
magnetic disks.
The technology is continuously being improved. Drives for the popular 5.25
inch diameter disks are now being replaced by drive units capable of running
cheaper and smaller 3.5 inch disks.
Furthermore, access times to the stored data are now down to 300
milliseconds and below, and manufacturers are moving the digital signal
processing from 16-bits to 32-bits, which will improve the access times and
data throughput.
Double-speed drive units now transfer data at 1.2 Megabytes a second, but
the quad-speed units currently being developed should bring this up to
around 4.8 Mbytes/sec.
Because CD technology combines high storage capacity and high data transfer
rates with low unit costs, it is particularly suitable for use with
graphics-based applications such video imaging and animation, which are
integral to multi media but need large storage capacity.
A single, whole-screen four-colour video image can take up as much as 2
Mbytes of space if uncompressed. so the storage needed for a typical video
clip makes the standard magnetic disk an expensive solution.
Other forms of mass storage will still be used for other existing areas.
Magnetic media in the form of both floppy and hard disks continue to
dominate the online storage marketplace, while tape drives, particularly the
Digital Audio Tape are making inroads into the data archiving market.
As multimedia evolves beyond its origins in entertainment and education, it
is likely to change the way we think about and use data. Developing this
technology will need huge amounts of data in a cheap, accessible and
reliable form. For storage capacity, access speeds and cost, the compact
disk in all its forms seems unlikely to be equalled for some time.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
