<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (9): Benefits outweigh problems -
Home-working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Doesn't your next door neighbour go to work any more?' remarks the nanny as
she comes up the drive. 'His car always seems to be here these days, lazy
old Rod]'
The answer is - yes and no. Rod next door works as hard as ever, but
increasingly, like many a salesperson, he does so at home. He sells Rank
Xerox photocopiers to the local government and health sector.
Rank Xerox has encouraged its sales staff to go home to work, starting with
a 'hot desk' policy of shared office space, and moving towards providing
them with home-based laptop computers. Xerox was one of the pioneers of the
idea (then only for top executives), 20 years ago. Now it is one of a
throng.
Independent and government-sponsored reports suggest that home-working is
already widely adopted, with 300,000 active teleworkers in the UK alone. The
Henley Centre for forecasting predicts at least 2,500,000 by 1995. The
Department of Trade and Industry and the Rural Development Commission
believe home-working technology can revitalise rural areas.
Here in rural Buckinghamshire, we have a microcosm of the social pattern of
the 1990s. Of the dozen houses in this hamlet, (not counting the farmhouse),
half the occupants are retired, and everyone in the other six households is
employed, five people in their own businesses, only one on the farm. Apart
from one, the businesses are all 'home-based.' Occupations are mixed: two
doctors, our Xerox neighbour, myself the journalist, a gardener, a caterer
and an electrical contractor.
Of these, I am as yet the only true 'teleworker,' working largely at home,
and entirely reliant on computer technology. My computer can connect to the
Financial Times' mainframe, and my telephone - most of the time - to the
rest of the world. This is written in a 'home office,' equipped with fax,
computer, laser printer, telephone and answering machine.
The technically self-sufficient home office (I like the term 'telebode') is
not to be confused with a telecottage, which is a fully equipped communal
resource in rural areas, for the use of anyone who has an occasional need of
technical resources and support. Such enterprises also train people for
teleworking, particularly women who are then qualified to take their skills
back to the most remote areas and become teleworkers.
The arrival of ISDN telephone technology gave Scotland a head start in
teleworking. Now widely available, ISDN is likely to lead to more
exploration of remote working, using teleconferencing and video-groupware to
link teleworkers, (see D for Desktop Video).
The term 'teleworker' suggests a reliance on technology, and is used to
describe those whose work is defined by the computer. The first pioneers
were unsurprisingly, in the area of computer programming.
The DTI has set up a voluntary Special Interest Group to raise awareness of
the potential of home-working - 'our job is to raise awareness, targeting
employers,' explains David Barry, chairman of Teleworking SIG. 'The
definition extends beyond users of groupware and those on networks to
include any home worker. Broadly speaking, productivity can be higher at
home: the new telematics technology offers potential savings on the
traditional office-based work pattern.'
As part of the Computer Supported Collaborative Workshop, the committee is
drawn from industry, consultants, practitioners and researchers.
Home-working is a source of cost-cutting to employers, who can make savings
on office space, travelling expenses, secretarial and administrative
support, and even employment costs if they use freelance teleworking
contractors.
Home workers save on the hassle of travel, have more time to work, and are
demonstrated to be more productive, working more flexibly and (not in this
house) without interruption. But not everyone is suited to the life:
solitary home workers have to be self-motivated, disciplined and
independent. One report found that remote clerical work simply wasn't a
success, because people partly came to work for the company, without which
the task became unbearable tedious.
In the 1990s, the leaps made in technology, and particularly in
communications, have meant that people can bring their work home with them,
yet stay in touch with the office, as never before. Large companies such as
NatWest, Sun Alliance and Unipart are sending their sales teams home,
equipped with laptops, motivated by regular contact on the network by
electronic mail.
It is more difficult for the self-employed to establish themselves. But
equipping a home office is easier and cheaper than ever before. The price of
hardware has plummeted, it has become better packaged, (plug-and-go) and
software has become far easier to use without training.
Nevertheless, for an IT novice, getting appropriate technical support can be
a formidable struggle, and an unforeseen expense. Some products are now
specifically tailored to the home market, such as the Arpeggio PC from Sonix
Communications in Cirencester, which provides ready-made instant
communication links, and cuts out the need for a permanent leased line.
Part of Canon UK's product range is aimed specifically at home workers, such
as its printers and the BN notebook range.
Despite some obvious disadvantages of teleworking, would I go back to
working 9am to 5.30pm, commuting to London? No thanks. I don't even need a
stroll round the bluebell woods to think about it . . .
Teleworking Explained; by British Telecom, tel 0800 800 854; Telecottage
Association, Freephone 0800 616 008; National Association of Teleworkers,
tel 0404 47467; Teleworking acceptance, benefits and management: OTR, on 071
402 3574; Teleworking in the 1990s - a view from the home: a research report
by Sussex University, tel 0273 678 165.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
