<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAGUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (7): Way to lift technology
burdens - Facilities Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Information technology (IT) is meant to be a tool that enables a company to
carry out its primary mission. The difficulty is that IT often threatens to
dominate budgets. The defence of the IT professional  - that you just cannot
get by without persistent technology expenditure - annoys company
accountants. A prudent business should be able to keep every cost under
control. If vital services, from car fleets to office cleaning, can be
contracted-out to third parties, why not IT?
Facilities management (FM) is the practice of hiving off computer services
to an outside supplier while the customer gets on with his prime business.
FM appears in guises such as systems integration, outsourcing and third
party maintenance (TPM). In 1992, the worldwide market for all such services
was estimated at Dollars 46.5bn, and predicted to grow to Dollars 108bn by
1997.
Some sectors are waking up to the potential for FM in a dramatic fashion. In
the telecoms realm, the European market for outsourced networks is estimated
at Dollars 11.7bn by 1997.
Saturn Global Networks (SGN), a specialist outsourcer for corporates needing
dedicated international datacomms, has just arrived in London, offering an
FM service on the much-vaunted information super-highway. SGN takes over
responsibility for tying up the intricate nodes that translate data at the
customer's end. The material is then fit to be flashed down the line and
across the globe. Each node costs around Dollars 75,000 to install, but
SGN's customers are not primarily concerned about cost. They want someone
else to handle the bits and bytes while they concentrate on their real
business.
FM offers to solve headaches by taking over the burden of technology. A
recent Dataquest survey of 500 senior European IT executives found that
gaining expertise and knowledge was regarded as the prime benefit of FM. But
when it came to choosing an FM supplier, the ability to deliver a solution
on time was the most significant factor.
The automated teller machine (ATM) is an indispensible part of retail
banking. Yet the Co-op Bank has elected to hand over its entire ATM network
to IBM in a Pounds 13.2m five-year contract. Mick Firth, director of retail
banking services at the Co-op, says cost is not a significant factor in this
radical move. He adds: 'We reviewed our distribution strategy. We wanted
increased functions, flexibility and the ability to guarantee quality of
service to the end user.'
The Co-op decided on a massive expansion of the ATM network, from 110
machines to a potential 500.
It started out with its own ATM network, and could have pursued this
strategy on its own. Mr Firth locates the real value of FM for his bank:
'We've avoided an extra investment, and we've freed resources we can use for
managing our branches.'
There are two rules to getting FM right, he says: one is to obtain a
watertight contract stipulating the level of service. The other is to create
a firm partnership with the FM supplier. 'The whole thing has worked very
successfully,' he notes. 'The handover took place in 20 days over February
and March.'
IBM is managing the entire operation, including cash replenishment. Co-op
customers will not see teams of programmers stuffing notes into the back of
their cash dispenser. But Securicor and Security Express staff will top up
the ATMs under contract to IBM.
The FM business continues to grow. Traditionally the computer industry has
generated huge profits from manufacturing hardware. This is the
'metal-bashing' side of the business - and makers of large computers have
suffered the same fate as other smokestack industries. Profits have
plummeted as smaller, more powerful systems brought down the price of
computing. The main suppliers have fled from their dependency on hardware
and are frantically diversifying into the lucrative world of FM. Bull has
placed its FM marketing drive under the umbrella of a new company, Athesa.
Local government, with its finances under relentless scrutiny, is a key
target. With 60 dedicated staff, Athesa will arrive on the customer's
doorstep as a specialist FM house. But the parent company will supply
personnel as soon as they are needed.
Bass Taverns is spending Pounds 3.9m (Dollars 5.7m) with Unisys in a
three-year outsourcing deal. Unisys will develop the software that runs
Bass' retailing system. With 2,500 pubs to support, this operation is the
lifeblood of Bass.
Writing and maintaining a customer's software has thrown up yet another IT
acronym: Applications Management (AM). Computer services group Hoskyns
claims AM to be the next big thing. But when Hoskyns commissioned a survey
of senior IT managers last year, 35 per cent still cited cost-containment as
their prime concern. It takes more than some snappy initials to blow away
the balance sheet blues. Contracting-out to an FM supplier may not guarantee
reduced spending, but it should keep the lid on.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7376 Computer Facilities Management.
    P7379 Computer Related Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
