<DOCNO>FT942-13141</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAGTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (8): Better ways of mapping the
data - GIS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you're a woman terrified of suffering a melanoma (skin cancer), move to
Brecon in Wales, where it hardly occurs. Men in Wales, however, suffer a
high incidence of stomach tumours, and cancers associated with sexual
behaviour. A report published at the end of March, The Atlas of Cancer
Incidence in England and Wales 1968-85 has for the first time examined the
locational occurrence of cancer, and identified many different forms with
specific locations.
This use of a Geographical Information System (GIS) illustrates how the
technique of mapping data to a physical location can reveal gems of
information. Based on data gathered over 18 years, the report has mapped
occurrences of different illnesses. The information may throw light on
causes and effects, and can certainly help to plan for health resources.
GIS has proved to be one of the boom areas of computing in the last years.
Newcomers include computer software houses, hardware suppliers, and
consultancies, all muscling in with determination on a territory that used
to be the cosy domain of geographical specialists. Once limited to expensive
dedicated equipment, the GIS is beginning to appear down-market, and become
a more accessible tool in commerce. Established IT giants - Sema Group,
Logica, Unisys, Informix and Oracle among them - are showing an interest in
the potential of GIS revenues.
Report and estimates about the boom in GIS have been appearing for some
time. According to the most recent results from IT researchers Dataquest,
published in March 1994, the total GIS market worldwide rose from Dollars
587m in 1992 to Pounds 654m in 1993.
'We anticipate a compound annual growth rate of 16 per cent per annum until
1995, which makes it one of the fastest growing areas of the software
markets,' says Petra Gartzen, a senior analyst and specialist in computer
aided design and GIS for the research group Dataquest. 'New applications and
technologies are constantly coming on the market, such as improved access to
satellite communicated data and geographical positioning systems (GPS).'
Some of the main areas in GIS are obvious: utilities recording assets, local
authorities planning future schools and services, road and transport
planning, retailers targeting their markets. Locational information has
become relevant in a world of compulsory competitive tendering, where
purchasing authorities 'outsource' to 'service providers.'
The GIS market is poised for its boom partly because the hard slog of the
groundwork - literally in the following case - has neared completion. In the
UK, the Ordnance Survey has been working for two decades creating the data.
Early efforts were not flexible enough for the emerging market. But in
November 1992, at the national conference of the Association for Geographic
Information, the OS announced Land-Line, the large scale digital map data
products which are at the heart of GIS user-systems around the country. They
have also now solved 'edge matching' - a problem where the paper-based
medium had stretched or shrunk so that the digitised versions did not quite
match when meeting on borders: 230,000 maps should be available in one
seamless whole by 1995.
One thing discovered by the early users of GIS is that the problems of
mapping data by location are by no means only technical. Viewing data
'spatially' has a fundamental effect on the way that organisations work.
Although there are great savings in cost and efficiency to be gained, the
investment of time, money and energy up-front produces expectations that may
take some time to come to fruition. The exercise of re-focusing operations
through a GIS is not unlike business process re-engineering: it involves
cross-disciplinary and departmental co-operation, and has to be driven from
the top.
This culture shock might explain why the market has shaped niche
specialisations. Strategic Mapping, MapInfo, and ESRI have all established
strong positions in the low-end market. ESRI's ARC/Info GIS has nearly half
the government GIS business worldwide, 27 per cent of the transportation
market, and over 20 per cent of the utilities.
In 1992 it is attributed with 35.7 per cent of worldwide software-only
sales: Intergraph, its nearest competitor is credited with 17.2 per cent.
Smallworld, the UK specialist based in Newmarket, has carved out a niche
with utilities - electricity, gas, water and telecommunications - by
offering a specialised 'hand-holding' service that eases the process of data
conversion, customisation, and business re-engineering. Its clients include
six cable companies, and seven out of the 12 UK electricity companies, and
has recently won a contract with German Bundespost.
Automated mapping and facilities management (AMFM) is specific to the
utilities providers which use it to map and define assets overground and
underground, and even in the air, to provide information on charging and
maintenance planning.
The largest sector in terms of market potential is business marketing and
sales, according to Dataquest's Petra Gartzen - 'we've done some analysis
about the business market because the technology has become so much more
accessible with powerful PCs. A lot of the business GIS is PC-based and we
anticipate that it will grow to Dollars 174m or more by 1997 from a humble
Dollars 10m in 1990.
'The market leaders are mainly US companies, Strategic Mapping and MapInfo;
overall leaders are Intergraph and ESRI. But the low end PC-based business
is where the growth is, penetrated by companies with an existing user-base
elsewhere, such as Autodesk.'
Visual information is becoming readily available. In March, President
Clinton overruled the CIA and ruled in favour of market forces, making
visual information commercially available from US satellites.
</TEXT>
