<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAGOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (2): New ways to use spare PC
power - Agent Software
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Software is set to go on the market to exploit the reservoir of untapped
energy existing in idle personal computers on desktops.
The history of the computer industry consistently proves the old maxim that
'nature abhors a vacuum.' No sooner do hardware engineers produce faster
chips and higher-capacity storage than software engineers rush in and create
new ways of using computers.
'There is an enormous amount of spare computing power out there and we are
on the verge of turning it loose with the next generation of multi-tasking
operating systems,' comments Mr David Friend, founder and chairman of Pilot
Software, a specialist in a new type of software called intelligent agents.
He adds: 'Imagine a large retailer with over 1,000 stores and maybe 30,000
different products in 800 categories. They need to collect sales data from
each store on a daily basis to get management information. They want to be
able to identify any product where sales have changed markedly,' he adds.
'They want to make sure they have hot items in stock . . . the problem is to
work out what mental rules you apply if you are an expert and define them
mathematically in a program so you can create a software agent - or agents -
to do the job. Then you can get that spare computer power working for you.'
The phenomenon of surplus computer power is, of course, relatively new.
Before the PC, computers were so expensive that all their power had to be
used to justify their cost. Mainframe systems were - and still are - used
for on-line work during the day and for batch processing at night.
With the spread of PCs, computer power has moved to the desktop and much of
it lies unused. The limitations of PCs are partly to blame. With some
exceptions, for instance background communications and printing, a PC can
only do one thing at a time.
But the move to multi-tasking operating systems such as Windows NT, OS/2 and
Unix opens the door to the latent power of the PC (see O for Operating
Systems).
Software agents can help to use this spare power productively. They are
either passive agents which monitor events and take action, or active agents
searching networks and databases for specific information.
A passive agent may monitor network traffic, measuring performance and
working to improve it.
Active agents help reduce the growing problem of information overload by
coping with the mass of information available in modern computer networks.
Typically, an active agent would use a set of rules to seek relevant
information for a project, consolidate it and present it to the user. This
type of agent fits well with developments in areas such as workgroup
computing (see W for Workgroups) and transaction management (see T for
Transaction Management).
The importance of agents as an enabling mechanism for these technologies
promises to open up a new software market. According to UK market researcher
Ovum, the worldwide market for agent software will grow from an annual value
of Dollars 37m in 1994 to Dollars 2.6bn by the year 2000.
Software builders have already started to add agents to a wide range of
applications.
One project aims to automate loan processing in an underwriting
organisation. As much as 80 per cent of the processing is carried out by
software agents, leaving the user to concentrate on exceptions and problems.
A project from Andersen Consulting, the world's biggest consulting firm,
uses agents to create a workbench which can filter newsfeeds and support
casual users in the financial services industry.
There are more ambitious plans for agents in the future. This year AT&amp;T
plans to introduce a messaging service called Personalink which uses agents
to filter messages and search for information on a network.
The agent software for Personalink was developed by General Magic, a
Californian-based software company founded by the two lead designers of the
Apple Macintosh. Telescript and Magic Cap, General Magic'stwo software
products, are at the core of the Personalink service and could become the
basis of more general standards in agent software.
Other leading players in the software agents market include IBM, Microsoft,
Hewlett Packard and Xerox.
With this level of interest and the expected market growth for agent
software, it will not be long before spare PC power begins to wane.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-13147</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAGNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Survey of A-Z of Computing (1): The revolution is about to
begin - Although millions of people use computers, new advances in
technology mean that the real computer revolution is only now about to start
/ Comment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The infrastructure of information technology is changing. The traditional
models of computing - either terminals controlled by a central computer or
stand-alone desktop personal computers - are giving way to a single model of
distributed power.
This year's Financial Times A to Z of Computing carries the theme of this
transition - to what some call the age of the 'network as the computer.'
Powerful desktop computers based on new chips - such as the Pentium and the
PowerPC - make it possible to provide almost every user with the local power
they need.
Multi-tasking operating systems like Windows NT, Unix and OS/2 offer access
to remote, shared resources such as printers and databases. Once plugged
into the emerging 'information highways,' the desktop computer becomes a
'window' on the IT world.
The emerging new infrastructure promises to open the door to many new
applications. Intelligent agent software which can scan a network of
databases, full-motion video, which can bring TV to the desktop computer,
and neural networks which can unravel complex data input, promise to extend
the boundaries of IT.
But while the new infrastructure makes many novel applications possible, it
also creates a new set of problems. Distributing computer power is not
enough. IT must also distribute functionality. This demands different
approaches to building IT systems and the software which makes them work.
Most important of all, IT systems must be tied closely to business needs.
Computer users are no longer satisfied with expensive systems which only
bring limited benefits. They want systems that are adaptable and can cope
with changes in the way their business is organised and administered.
New techniques such as business process re-engineering and workgroup
computing are expected to make it easier to build enterprise-wide
applications and deliver genuine benefits. When combined with software
engineering tools and object-oriented design, these new analysis techniques
should make it possible to create flexible applications which can change
with the business.
But it is not only big business which will gain from the new IT
infrastructure. PC technology is increasingly finding a place in the home -
either to support 'teleworking' in a home office or as a domestic aid for
'teleshopping,' managing personal finances and entertainment. Laptop
computers plugged into the 'information highway' will extend computing to
every corner of our lives.
The move to the new infrastructure will not be without pain, of course.
Those who hold on to the past will find it increasingly difficult to find a
market for their skills. But there are some ideas from the past which will
survive and help to solve some of the technical problems created by the new
infrastructure.
The valuable lessons learned in the mainframe era - particularly those
associated with managing transaction traffic and data storage or methods for
controlling software - offer proven solutions and should not be ignored.
'After 40 years of constant change, glowing predictions and never-ending
complexity, computers are finally being used by millions of people worldwide
every day. In spite of this, the computer revolution is only now about to
begin,' says Mr David Vaskevitch, director of enterprise computing at
Microsoft, in his recently-published book Client/Server Strategies.
He is right. The computer revolution he predicts promises to be one of the
most exciting technological changes in human history.
This year's Financial Times A to Z of Computing is your guide to this
change.
</TEXT>
