</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: AB disappoints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRIS PRICE and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Disappointment at the lack of news at Associated British Foods was said to
be behind the 15 pence fall in the shares to 583p, despite profit figures in
line with market expectations. Turnover was an unusually heavy 1.1m.
Many analysts had been hopeful that the acquisitive and cash rich company
might use yesterday's profits statement to announce another deal, following
the rumours of a bid for the cake business of Allied Lyons mooted recently
in the market. Allied Lyons shares slipped 3 to 587p.
Enterprise Oil came under moderate pressure, closing 3 off at 445p as bid
stories, and suggestions that a rights issue would be needed to fund such a
move, continued to circulate.
British Gas shares dropped 9 to 297p in unspectacular turnover of 6.1m as
the market prepared itself for the consultative paper expected from Ofgas,
the industry regulator, on competition, rate of return and the new price cap
formula on transport tariffs.
The latest improvement in crude oil prices gave the majors a strong boost.
BP touched 392p early in the session before slipping back to close a net 2
1/2 ahead at 388p on heavy turnover of 14m.
There was widespread gloom in the bank sector where dealers reported
persistent profit-taking following last week's surge of interest in the wake
of the Lloyds Bank bid for the Cheltenham and Gloucester Building Society.
Standard Chartered dipped 14 to 995p as the market remained unconvinced that
Lloyds would hold on to its near 5 per cent stake. Lloyds shares lost 8 to
589p on profit-taking. Abbey National, hit last week by worries that the
Lloyds move would trigger a war in the mortgage market, rallied 5 to 437p.
Pharmaceuticals group Glaxo suffered the biggest fall among the FT-SE 100
stocks, the shares tumbling 3.6 per cent as the market focused on weekend
press coverage of a lengthy review of the company's prospects by leading US
brokerage Salomon Brothers.
Salomon's Mr Peter Laing has argued that Glaxo will have to include Pounds
500m of provisions in its 1996 figures as a result of redundancies from the
decline of Zantac, the anti-ulcer treatment which accounts for the largest
proportion of sales. Mr Laing has also reduced his 1996 forecast excluding
provisions by Pounds 305m to Pounds 2.075bn. The shares slid 21 to 554p.
SmithKline Beecham's last annual meeting hosted by Mr Bob Bauman failed to
inspire and the shares shed 6 to 376p. However Wellcome held steady to close
only 2 weaker at 513p as analysts anticipated US approval for the company's
anti-epileptic drug Lamictal.
London International eased a further 2 to 103p ahead of an announcement that
Powerstock, an investment arm of Malaysian Genting, had increased its stake
to 4.4 per cent.
The electricity distribution companies, known in the market as 'recs',
suffered from another flurry of heavy selling by institutions and private
investors increasingly worried by the electricity industry regulator's much
tougher than expected opening stance on pricing proposals for next year.
Hints of the regulator's severe stance leaked into the market last Friday,
triggering big falls across the sector.
Among the worst casualties yesterday were the two FT-SE constituents,
Eastern, 16 off at 600p and Southern, 21 lower at 580p. Manweb lost 20 to
672p and Seeboard 17 to 308p.
In a lacklustre stores sector, Sears were strong ahead of results today. The
shares put on 3 to 131 1/2 p. Analysts have pencilled in around Pounds 127m
for this morning's full-year figures.
News and information group Reuters Holdings lifted 13 to 518p after the
company announced a 15 per cent jump in first quarter revenues.
</TEXT>
