<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was a largely dull session in the futures and options market yesterday,
with thin trading and few noteworthy features, writes Christopher Price.
Dealers reported a lack of buying or selling interest almost from the start,
and the June contract on the FTSE 100 spent most of the session drifting
slowly down. In fact, June's opening trade at 3,138 turned out to be the
high of the day, after which a lack of buying enthusiasm rather than selling
pressure saw June slip back.
GDP figures in line with market expectations stemmed the drift for a short
time, but the weak gilts market continued be a negative influence and June
continued to lose ground.
A weak opening on Wall Street added to the slide and June hit 3,101 shortly
before the close, its low of the day. A slight spurt towards the finish saw
June end the session at 3,102 with volume a lowly 10,128 contracts.
However, in after hours trading, June brightened up, reflecting a turnaround
in sentiment on Wall Street, the contract ticking up to 3,109.
Lasmo topped the stock options list once more - at 2,269 contracts, with
takeover talk again said to be inspiring investors' interest. Glaxo was
second at 1,072. Total options volume was 18,414 contracts, compared with
over 29,000 on Friday.
</TEXT>
