<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Markets Report: Dollar slips lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The dollar fell back on foreign exchanges yesterday as the weekend G7
meeting failed to produce any statement supportive of the currency, writes
Philip Gawith.
The flip side of dollar weakness was D-Mark strength and the German currency
finished stronger across the board. In London the dollar closed at DM1.6794
against the D-Mark from DM1.6947 on Friday.
The D-Mark was helped by comments from a Bundesbank council member
cautioning that German interest rates might not fall as fast as some
countries wanted.
Sterling also suffered at the hands of the stronger D-Mark, closing at
DM2.5049 from DM2.517 on Friday. It was slightly firmer against the dollar,
finishing at Dollars 1.4916 from Dollars 1.4853. The sterling index closed
at 79.9, from 80.
Although Japanese officials made clear at the G7 meeting that they were
unhappy with the level of the yen, many analysts believe that the US
administration is satisfied with the current exchange rate.
Mr Paul Chertkow, head of global currency research at UBS, said some members
of the Clinton administration appeared to believe that they had Japan on the
ropes - 'that if you squeeze them so hard they have to open their markets
finally.'
He said it was arguable that Japanese economic recovery was not possible at
the current exchange rate, while if the dollar fell below Y100, this was
'armageddon'.
There was little market response yesterday to the confirmation of Mr Tsutomu
Hata as the new prime minister. The yen finished at Y103.225 from Y103.650.
Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at DKB International, said this was because
Mr Hata's premiership was unlikely to impact on economic policy or the trade
dispute, nor resolve political uncertainty.
Mr Chertkow, however, predicted that Mr Hata would try to placate the US by
enshrining the 1994/5 budget cuts as permanent, while the Bank of Japan
would support this fiscal stimulus by cutting rates again. He added that if
the economy did not recover, Mr Hata's coalition government would be
unlikely to survive.
Mr Lyons said the yen/dollar rate might remain in the spotlight ahead of the
golden week holiday which starts on Friday in Japan, and lasts most of the
following week.
The UBS analyst said the US/Japan trade dispute 'continues to cast a pall
over the dollar generally.' Having fallen below DM1.6840 against the dollar
the US currency is next expected to test the DM1.6650 level.
A number of other factors weighed on the US currency. One, according to Mr
Tony Norfield, UK treasury economist at ABN-AMRO, was a delayed response to
Friday's appointment of two new Fed board members. The market believes this
will give the Fed a more doveish flavour, and hence slow the rate of
monetary tightening.
Another was the general firming of European interest rates. This is the
result of more bullish economic forecasts emerging from Germany, which has
encouraged a bearish tone in German interest rate markets.
This was evident in the futures markets, with the June euromark contract
settling three basis points lower at 94.72. The back-end contracts lost more
ground, with the December 1995 contract losing 20 basis points.
Traders stressed, however, that these movements in the longer contracts were
deceptive as most of the trade was amongst locals. Lack of liquidity also
made the contracts susceptible to manipulation. Weakness at the short end of
the yield curve is also a spillover from the longer end, where sentiment in
bund futures has soured.
The fall in euromark futures was reflected in short sterling futures. The
June contract finished six points down at 94.57. Markets are now discounting
mid-year short term interest rates  1/2 of a percentage point higher than in
January.
The longer contracts dropped further, with the December future finishing 16
basis points worse at 93.78. In the money market, the Bank of England
provided late assistance of about Pounds 225m. Earlier the Bank had provided
Pounds 727m liquidity compared to a forecast shortage of Pounds 950m.
Overnight money traded in the 4 1/4 per cent-5 3/4 per cent range.
Sterling was unaffected by the GDP and trade data released. Preliminary
first quarter GDP growth was 0.7 per cent, quarter on quarter, in line with
market estimates. The non-EU trade deficit for March was Pounds 675m,
compared with February's revised Pounds 640m.
The D-Mark finished higher across the board in Europe. It closed at L957.7
against the Italian lira, from L956.7, and Pta81.52 from Pta81.37 against
the Spanish peseta.
The French franc fell below its old ERM floor again to finish at FFr3.435
from FFr3.427. Analysts said market sentiment was turning against the franc
owing to the Bank of France's tardy pace of monetary easing. The issue will
acquire fresh relevance when new unemployment figures are released on
Friday.
</TEXT>
