<PROFILE>_AN-EDZEDAF7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture (Farmer's Viewpoint): Dutch
agriculture faces a Herculean task - Over-stocking farm land with animals
has created a problem of Augean proportions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID RICHARDSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Dr Ir van Dijk has three academic qualifications and three jobs.
He is professor of agricultural co-operation at Wageningen University,
director general of the Dutch National Co-operative Council and chairman of
the International Agricultural Strategy Council for the Dutch government.
But when I met him a few days ago he had his arm up the back of one of his
pedigree Texel ewes which was having difficulty lambing.
It must be said that he and his family have only a small flock at their old
farmhouse in the Dutch village of Lienden and that the sheep are kept more
for a hobby than as a business. But it was immediately clear that in spite
of the long list of letters after his name this was a practical man who
understood farming.
I visited Prof van Dijk to learn about 'Ter Zake', of which he is one of the
authors and which literally translated means 'To Work'. It is a rallying
call to Dutch farmers to get on with sorting out their problems themselves
rather than relying on the European Union or the Dutch government. It
epitomises the purpose of a 'great debate' now under way across the rural
areas of The Netherlands on future policies for farming.
For although Dutch farmers have a long-standing reputation for being among
the most innovative and efficient in Europe they are now, as Prof van Dijk
explained to me, facing declining incomes, severe environmental restrictions
and a deteriorating relationship with the Dutch public. The Great Debate, he
hopes, will identify and define these problems so that obvious solutions may
emerge and ancillary organisations and businesses can get 'to work' on
implementing them.
There can be no doubt that Dutch agriculture is in crisis. Unlike British
farmers, who have seen incomes rise during the past two years, incomes in
The Netherlands have continued their downward trend. Moreover the Dutch
experience is what the authors of the reform of the EU's common agricultural
policy intended. British farmers' good fortune is, to a large extent, the
result of the devaluation of sterling in September 1992 and the subsequent
statutory adjustments to green currencies to bring UK farm prices up, by
some 20 per cent, to their real value compared with other EU currencies.
During earlier years, in the 1970s and 1980s, Dutch farmers had overcome the
shortcomings of their small-farm structure by intensifying their management
methods, especially with livestock. Dutch traders discovered alternative
animal feed ingredients, such as manioc from Thailand, which could be
cheaply imported from third countries, by-passing EU tariff restrictions.
Dutch food processors developed markets for farm produce all over the world.
And in spite of its small land area, The Netherlands became one of the
biggest exporters of agricultural goods in the world.
But animal feed, once it has passed through the animal, turns into dung.
There are now so many animals on Dutch farms eating so much imported feed
that the business of disposing of their wastes on the limited land available
has become unbalanced. Indeed critics have suggested that some areas in the
east and south of the country are like a gigantic sewage farm.
Inevitably this has led to environmental problems. Soils have become so
overburdened with certain minerals that they have become a pollution hazard.
In spring, when animal slurry, stored all winter, is spread, or as is now
decreed, injected into the land, the smell across wide areas of the country
is unpleasant, even to a farmer's nose.
Attempts have been made to contain the problem by limiting the number of
animals kept on each farm and by government regulations on the quantity of
slurry applied to land. But the restrictions were applied after the animal
population had reached unmanageable proportions and there has so far been no
serious move to cut livestock numbers.
The Great Debate has at least resulted in this possibility being discussed -
although the current priority seems to be to find some way to feed pigs, for
instance, so that they produce lower mineral levels in their dung. The fact
that exports of intensively-produced livestock are so important to the Dutch
balance of payments is clearly significant to the debate.
It goes without saying that this intensity of livestock production has been
significant in the deterioration of Dutch farmers' public relations.
The Great Debate has been going on for several months now. Every region and
every sector of Dutch agriculture and horticulture has been involved and
some preliminary conclusions are, apparently being reached.
Quite apart from the excess of livestock it has, for instance, been admitted
that there are too many abattoirs in the country and some kind of
rationalisation seems to be on the cards. The farm supply trade, dominated
as it is by co-operatives, has recognised that it is overmanned. The three
farmers' unions representing Catholics, Protestants and Liberals have begun
to talk of forming one federation.
A recent survey has indicated a growing acceptance among Dutch farmers that
they need to farm in more environment-friendly ways. Prof van Dijk told me
of new targets to reduce farm emissions of potentially polluting chemicals,
minerals and gasses by between 70 and 80 per cent. Exactly what that means
in terms of inputs and in turn production is not yet entirely clear,
although establishing this is exercising the minds of Dutch agricultural
economists.
Some of the 100,000 farmers in The Netherlands have begun to realise that
there may not be an adequate living for more than half that number by the
end of the century.
The growing self-awareness that appears to be coming about as the Great
Debate progresses is being achieved through discussion and without
confrontation. And it is beginning to lead to pragmatic decisions by
individuals and groups.
Some are addressing problems with a view to beating them. Others are
planning to get out of business while they still have time.
All in all the debate seems to be a catalyst for change. And although the
British farming industry is nothing like as intensive and does not yet face
the same degree of crisis, I feel sure that it would benefit from a similar
self-examination.
</TEXT>
