<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / World Commodities Prices: Coffee futures hold firm - Market
Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Commodity Exchange COFFEE futures held firm in thin trading yesterday
as investors looked ahead to today's meeting between the Brazilian officials
and coffee growers over the government's plan to sell official stocks.
'Until that's out of the way, no one is prepared to take a view on the
market,' one trader said.
The July position closed at Dollars 1,496 a tonne, up Dollars 23 but well
short of the recent high.
There was no reaction to news that the robusta coffee retention indicator
had passed the 70 cents-a-pound mark, allowing sales of beans stockpiled
under the producer's market support scheme.
COCOA prices lost ground in the afternoon. Early industry buying was
confined to bargain-hunting and failed to follow prices up, traders said. By
the close the July price had retreated from a high of Pounds 888 a tonne to
Pounds 874, down Pounds 6 on the day.
Base metals trading at the London Metal Exchange remained slow. COPPER ended
steadier but with the three months delivery prices below the earlier high of
Dollars 1,930 a tonne as a lack of follow-through interest and a downturn in
the New York market prompted profit-taking and speculative selling.
ALUMINIUM also slipped from earlier highs as resistance and selling emerged
towards Dollars 1,300 a tonne for three months delivery. It was last at
Dollars 1,291.50, up Dollars 4.50.
Compiled from Reuter
</TEXT>
