<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Government Bonds: Bunds fall as focus remains on economic
growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
German bund futures fell back over a point as the market continued to focus
on the prospect of economic growth and the likelihood of another high money
supply figure to be released this week. The market chose to ignore the
release of favourable inflation figures yesterday, maintaining a bearish
mood, and as bund prices tumbled, they dragged the other European government
bond markets down in their wake.
The German market is anxiously awaiting the release today by the leading
economic research institutes of their growth forecasts for 1994, dealer
said.
Bond analysts and dealers said that the market has chosen to focus on recent
comments by German politicians and Bundesbank officials suggesting that
economic growth may be picking up. Last week, Mr Rexrodt, the Economics
Minister, said growth could even be somewhat better than forecast.
Yesterday, Bundesbank board member Mr Edgar Meister was reported saying
there were signs of recovery in the west German economy.
Some economists at investment banks, meanwhile, have revised their growth
forecasts upwards. As a result, the bund market is nervous that the
Bundesbank could slow down or halt its already snail-pace easing in
short-term rates.
Meanwhile, the M3 money supply figures for March are due to be released this
week. After the annualised 17.5 per cent growth in February, dealers expect
the March figure still to be in double-digits and well above the
Bundesbank's 4 to 6 per cent target range.
With the economic recovery and M3 figures providing the main focus, the
release of favourable inflation figures was largely ignored by the market.
April inflation figures from North Rhine-Westphalia were better than
expected, with annual CPI growth slowing to 3.0 per cent from 3.1 per cent
in March, while the monthly increase remained unchanged at 0.2 per cent.
This follows the release on Friday of the inflation figures from the state
of Baden-Wuerttemberg where inflation was up 0.3 per cent on the month and
3.1 per cent on the year.
The Liffe bund futures contract opened at 94.74 and fell to 93.58 before
settling at 93.65.
The drop in bund prices depressed the other European government bond
markets, pushing French debt prices lower in the absence of significant
domestic factors.
Swedish government bonds tracked the bund market lower, but saw additional
downward pressure as a result of the disappointing 'mini-budget' announced
yesterday. One analyst pointed out that many of the measures announced in
the supplementary budget are due to be phased in over a long period of time
and could be jeopardised by the autumn general election.
In addition, the Swedish bond market has seen heavy new supply - both of
index-linked and of conventional stock - in recent days, which dealers said
had weighed down the market.
Short-dated UK gilts opened on a soggy note ahead of Wednesday's auction,
while the decline in bund prices further depressed the market, leading to a
fall of a point from the previous close.
The release of the economic growth figures was in line with expectations and
dealers said the gilt market chose to ignore the domestic economic data and
focus on the bund market's decline instead.
Britain's gross domestic product rose 0.7 per cent in the first quarter from
the fourth quarter of 1993 and was up 2.6 per cent compared with the same
period a year earlier.
The Liffe gilt futures contract fell from 106.26 at the opening to a low of
105.26, settling at 106.09.
Longer-dated US Treasuries posted solid gains yesterday afternoon as traders
followed through on last week's encouraging rebound. The improvement
followed a decision by the Treasury to postpone Wednesday's supply auction
in honor of former President Richard Nixon, who died at the weekend.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  13/16 better
at 89. The yield eased to 7.145 per cent, 27 basis points lower than at last
Monday's close. The two-year note was off  1/16 at 99 3/16 , to yield 5.555
per cent.
Bonds generally meandered in directionless trading for most of the morning.
There was little economic news to drive the market, but a weakening trend in
US securities overseas cast a shadow.
Traders were unruffled by news of a 5.7 per cent rise in sales of existing
homes last month, after a 9.6 per cent fall in February. The recovery
offered no convincing evidence of a fresh surge in housing activity nor an
unsettling escalation of inflationary pressure.
On the contrary, the market grew bolder in the conviction that the economy
was not as strong as it had feared just a fortnight ago. Although there was
no further indication of a slowdown, the long bond climbed steadily during
the afternoon.
</TEXT>
