<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / International Capital Markets: IFC in plan to securitise
emerging market loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The International Finance Corporation, the World Bank's private sector
finance arm, plans to securitise part of its emerging market loan porfolio.
'We have a scheme under design which would allow us to pool selected
corporate project loans as collateral to issue rated securities', said Mr
Richard Frank, the IFC's chief financial officer. The loans involved will be
located in Latin America and Asia.
The IFC is in discussion with credit rating agencies to agree the level of
enhancement required to support issuing high-grade securities. 'We are
looking for high-quality securities on the basis of the loan pool collateral
and supporting features,' Mr Frank said.
One difficulty is that while the corporate borrowers are investment grade,
they may be located in sub-investment grade countries, he said.
Taking existing loans off its balance sheet through securitisation will
allow the IFC to increase its loan capacity.
'There is a high level of demand for our funding, and this will allow us to
finance a larger volume of loans,' he said.
The IFC's disbursed and outstanding loan portfolio totals some Dollars 5bn,
of which 42 per cent is Latin American and 23 per cent Asian.
The initial scheme would involve about Dollars 300 to Dollars 400m in
corporate loans, but as the IFC disburses more loans it may create new pools
for securitisation, Mr Frank said.
</TEXT>
