FT  26 APR 94 / International Bonds: Minimal issue supply in choppy
conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Choppy conditions in the underlying government bond markets kept Eurobond
issuance to a bare minimum.
'It's not a very constructive environment - investors are still very, very
cautious and although we've seen some nibbling, the markets are still
fragile,' said one syndicate manager.
The Canadian dollar sector saw the bulk of yesterday's meagre supply:
CDollars 165m of 10-year bonds for the Municipality of Metropolitan Toronto
via ScotiaMcLeod, and CDollars 150m of two-year notes for Landesbank
Schleswig-Holstein via Nomura. Both deals were targetted mainly at
continental European retail investors and medium-sized institutions but
neither issue met heavy demand, traders said.
The sterling sector was abuzz with talk of imminent 10-year issues, but a
volatile gilt market kept investors and issuers firmly on the sidelines.
Eastern Electric was rumoured to be planning a Pounds 350m 10-year deal via
CS First Boston and BZW. Abbey National and Cable &amp; Wireless were also
tipped as possible issuers.
Elsewhere, there was talk that Sweden is poised to issue Y100bn of five-year
Euroyen bonds, although dealers warned there would not be enough demand for
such a large deal. Belgium was also expected to bring its widely rumoured
French franc issue, some said as early as today.
</TEXT>
