<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / International Company News: Price for UAP public offer set
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French government yesterday announced a price of FFr152 per share for
the public offer of the privatisation of Union des Assurances de Paris, the
country's largest insurance group.
The price represents a discount of about 7 per cent to yesterday's close of
FFr164 for UAP shares. Industry analysts said that the price was at the
lower end of expectations.
The French government also announced a group of long-term stable
shareholders which will hold a combined 11 per cent of UAP's shares.
Compagnie Generale des Eaux, the construction and communications group will
hold 2.2 per cent of UAP's shares, as will Soparinvest, part of the Albert
Frere group of Belgium and Germany's Westdeutsche Landesbank.
Saint-Gobain, the French glass and building materials group will hold 1.2
per cent of the shares, while Peugeot Citroen, the vehicle group will hold
0.8 per cent.
Meiji Mutual Life of Japan will take 1 per cent, with the balance accounted
for by Credit Local de France, the local authority lender, and the Caisse
des Depots, the state financial institution.
In addition to the core shareholders named yesterday, Banque Nationale de
Paris will hold 15 per cent of UAP's capital, reducing its stake from the
current level of 19 per cent.
Under the terms of the issue, individual investors will be able to confirm
orders for UAP shares from this morning until the evening of May 3. In the
case of excess demand for the 47.3m shares reserved for individuals, there
will be a clawback of up to 15 per cent of the 47.3m shares allotted to the
offering for institutional investors.
French insurers, Page 31
